<p>11/4 23:00 PDT, Building 328, Codename ‚ÄúStelarc‚Äù, ground-based <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/laser%20guide%20star" title="Wikipedia: laser guide star">laser guide star</a>, R. Grosseteste<a href="#fn23" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref23"><sup>23</sup></a>, sup.</p>
<p>11/9 18:00 PDT, Site 600, Codename ‚Äú<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taliesin" title="Wikipedia: Taliesin">Taliesin</a>‚Äù, 80 kiloton, B. Dietz &amp; P. Quine, sup.</p>
<p>‚ÄúMechanics are the Paradise of mathematical science, because here we [pg25] come to the fruits of mathematics.‚Äù LdV<a href="#fn24" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref24"><sup>24</sup></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚ÄìLooks like we‚Äôre real, said Thorpe.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôre lucky. It was years before I was associated with a shot.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIs that luck?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs a bit of a prestige. A merit badge<a href="#fn25" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref25"><sup>25</sup></a>.</p>
<p>Quine cleared the screen and brought up the Superbright test data.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou see. Intense brightness here, and here. Very erratic pattern.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThis data is picked up how?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhen the bomb ignites, radiation from the rods bounces off some reflectors to</p>
<p>‚ÄìX-ray mirrors?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, something like that. They‚Äôre <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/beryllium" title="Wikipedia: beryllium">beryllium</a>. The data agrees with theory to a point, but when we increase power, we don‚Äôt get an increase in beam, in fact we get less. We‚Äôve talked about trying different metals in the rods, we‚Äôve used gold till now, but mercury‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìYeah, elements seventy-two through ninety-five would be good to try but with the, you know, time constraints, I checked and Fabrication has gold rods ready to go, so maybe those are a good choice and you can, or I mean we can sort of concentrate on sensor configuration‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìSounds reasonable.</p>
<p>Thorpe continued to stare at the screen. ‚ÄìCould this be an <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Annulus%20%28mathematics%29" title="Wikipedia: Annulus (mathematics)">annular</a>? This pattern I mean, could those reflectors be picking up a sort of imperfect focus, you know, the edge of a ring? If we move them in‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôve tried, no luck.</p>
<p>‚ÄìCan I look at your focusing code?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, sure, all the files are in this directory.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs great. Mind if I work here? pointing to Null‚Äôs desk.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAh, sure. Sure, go ahead. I‚Äôm going for lunch and maybe a swim.<a href="#fn26" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref26"><sup>26</sup></a> I‚Äôll see you later.</p>
<p><em>We read of the beaver that when it is pursued, knowing that it is for the medicinal virtue of its testicles and not being able to escape, it stops; and it bites off its testicles with its sharp teeth and leaves them to its enemies.</em><a href="#fn27" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref27"><sup>27</sup></a></p>
<hr/>
<p>Gaunt, saturnine, Bran Nolan in a corner of the cafeteria looked up unsmiling from scattered papers to raise a hand in greeting. [pg26]</p>
<p>‚ÄìHow‚Äôs our new boyo Kihara?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWeren‚Äôt you in line for that position?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs my Tourette‚Äôs syndrome. Terrible liability in a press officer, never know what he might blurt out in public.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou should have been asked.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you know, I‚Äôm happier, if that‚Äôs the word I want, where I am. Kihara is a little lamb. The last man, Vessell, didn‚Äôt outlast Slater. And we‚Äôre not done with all that, no indeed.</p>
<p>‚ÄìGetting some work done? Quine indicated the papers.</p>
<p>‚Äì‚ÄúThe Lab has a longstanding commitment to developing new methods and technologies to protect the environment‚Äù, the most effective of which to date has been the press release. Do you know we have a toxics mitigation program now? Seems there‚Äôs a toxic plume seeping into the groundwater under a vineyard off the north boundary. Vines died, soil went gray, the whole field stinks like sepsis. I‚Äôm writing an upbeat report about it. And yourself? How‚Äôs the death ray coming?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWe can maim small insects at a meter. The new concept is interceptors. Small flying rocks.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you know, da Vinci invented <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shrapnel%20shell" title="Wikipedia: Shrapnel shell">shrapnel</a><a href="#fn28" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref28"><sup>28</sup></a>. He‚Äôd have been right at home here with all these advanced minds.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, that‚Äôs Highet‚Äôs conceit.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThrowing rocks at things. We should be proud, thinking about these old impulses in such an advanced way.</p>
<p>A plump figure came forward shaking a sheaf of papers, from which Nolan recoiled. ‚ÄìBran, Bran, Bran. What must I do to get you to use a font other than <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Courier%20%28typeface%29" title="Wikipedia: Courier (typeface)">Courier</a>?</p>
<p>‚ÄìHello Bob, how‚Äôs the gout? I don‚Äôt like this business of tarting up manuscripts. You get enchanted by the beauty of it all. You start to think you‚Äôre writing the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book%20of%20Kells" title="Wikipedia: Book of Kells">Book of Kells</a>.</p>
<p>‚ÄìA few attractive fonts, tastefully applied, can spice up a presentation. A little <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/humanitas" title="Wikipedia: humanitas">humanitas</a>, you know. Why else, Bran, did we get you that powerful and costly <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/workstation" title="Wikipedia: workstation">workstation</a>?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt know, Bob, why did you? I was still figuring out the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM%20Selectric%20typewriter" title="Wikipedia: IBM Selectric typewriter">type balls on my Selectric</a>.</p>
<p>The sheaf of papers fell fanning from their clip onto the table. [pg27]</p>
<p>Shaking his head and chuckling grimly, Bob passed on to another table.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHumanitas, yes, that‚Äôs what we need here, isn‚Äôt it, Highet with his Renaissance, and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aldus%20Manutius" title="Wikipedia: Aldus Manutius">Aldus Manutius</a> there, need a few more particle men who‚Äôve read the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tao%20Te%20Ching" title="Wikipedia: Tao Te Ching">Tao Te Ching</a><a href="#fn29" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref29"><sup>29</sup></a>, couple more managers who‚Äôve studied <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun%20Tzu" title="Wikipedia: Sun Tzu">Sun Tzu</a>, lend these binary views a little tone, dress up the winners and losers, the Elect and the Preterite<a href="#fn30" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref30"><sup>30</sup></a>, the screwers and the screwed. Each man in his station, and keep your distance from the low life, can‚Äôt have just anyone winning, because if you ever let the rabble ahead, if they can rise, you can surely fall.</p>
<p>Nolan folded back pages, ‚Äìlisten to this bit, ‚Äúthe support of this tight-knit community‚Äù, support is it now? I‚Äôd have said the goading, the ambition, the Schadenfreude, that‚Äôs what gets the work done. The wife walked out six months ago with the kid, you‚Äôre eating Campbell‚Äôs soup cold out of the can, you haven‚Äôt got a clean shirt, but after a few months of eighteen hour days you‚Äôve got <em>data</em> that everyone wants to see. You <em>win big</em>.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBran, you work here, too.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat should I do then, write novels? Or maybe journalism, that‚Äôs it, <em>investigative</em> journalism. Have you met the journalist from Cambridge? Right over there with his tape recorder, name‚Äôs <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh%20Gusterson" title="Wikipedia: Hugh Gusterson">Armand Steradian</a>. He‚Äôs researching the belief systems of those who work on weapons of mass destruction<a href="#fn31" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref31"><sup>31</sup></a>, I think that was his phrase. Quite the charmer. He‚Äôs published one book on scientific fraud, and a paper highly critical of what he calls the defense establishment. You probably don‚Äôt watch TV but there was a program on PBS last night, Steradian was in it abusing R√©ti.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDoes Highet know he‚Äôs here?</p>
<p>‚ÄìHighet invited him.<a href="#fn32" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref32"><sup>32</sup></a></p>
<p>Quine headed for the door, passing as he did Armand Steradian, who held a small microphone before a J Section technician, ‚Äìyou‚Äôre so goldang busy every day you just put off thinking about it, though in Quine‚Äôs view pressure was a tool well used to put off thinking.</p>
<hr/>
<p>Black cottonwoods around the pool throve despite the drought. Their catkins littered the water. A jet moved on the sky, stitching a contrail [pg28] across a lace of cloud where a white sun struggled. Quine sat on a towel on the grassy verge and watched a portly swimsuited man enter through the gate, barrel chest glossed with hair, and behind him a woman in a white halter top and shorts, the heads of three men turning to follow. The pool was crowded this Friday afternoon; it was warm, it was the end of the workweek, it was family day; unlike Quine, most worked a five day week, most would depart hence into a forgetfulness. In the shallows of the pool two young girls splashed. One opened her mouth to show her companion a bright penny on her outstretched tongue. A young mother in a black maillot gripped a ladder to raise herself half from the pool and wave at her infant in a nearby stroller, glisten and shadow in the cords of her back, and Quine suffered a pang for a life now beyond his knowing: to be wed, with child, so young. On thermals a black and white winged vulture, <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cathartes%20aura" title="Wikipedia: Cathartes aura">Cathartes aura</a></em>, rocked and banked. From the jet thunder fell like muffled blows. The warmth and the sound of water churned by swimmers and the spray tossed up by their passing lulled Quine into a lethargy from which he woke with a start to consult his watch. On the pool‚Äôs floor danced cusps of light.</p>
<hr/>
<p>The caf√©‚Äôs walls rose past exposed beams and ducts to the nacre of frosted skylights. Lynn sat in a wirebacked chair at a glass table, face downcast at papers before her. In the moment before she looked up, Kate‚Äôs face glowed before him. What do you do, Philip?</p>
<p>‚ÄìHoy es el <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/d%C3%ADa%20de%20los%20muertos" title="Wikipedia: d√≠a de los muertos">d√≠a de los muertos</a>, Lynn said in greeting, banishing Kate‚Äôs image. Angularities all her own moved in her flesh; a small gap showed between her teeth as she smiled.</p>
<p>Quine seated himself and said gravely, ‚ÄìI should tell you I‚Äôm involved with someone.</p>
<p>‚ÄìGee, I said I wanted to apologize, not start an affair.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI, sorry I‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìAnd maybe pick your brain about Radiance.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm sorry, I, what did you say before? El d√≠a‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìToday is the Day of the Dead. All Saint‚Äôs Day. All of California used to be Mexico, you know, they called it <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aztl%C3%A1n%23Use%20by%20the%20Chicano%20movement" title="Wikipedia: Aztl√°n#Use by the Chicano movement">Aztlan</a>. Once my group shuts the Lab down, we‚Äôre going to reclaim Aztlan for the native peoples [pg29]. Oh, don‚Äôt look that way, I‚Äôm joking, that‚Äôs the kind of thing the far right says about us.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYour group?</p>
<p>‚ÄìCitizens Against Nuclear Technology<a href="#fn33" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref33"><sup>33</sup></a>. I‚Äôm a paralegal with them.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat‚Äôs that you‚Äôre reading?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYour press releases. She held a sheaf set in unadorned Courier font. ‚ÄìYou people have fingers in a lot of pies. When I started my concern was the bombs, but that‚Äôs just the tip of the iceberg, isn‚Äôt it. There‚Äôs also the supercomputers, the lasers, the genetics, the chemicals‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou probably know more about it than I do.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYour cover stories are so creative. Every one of. Oh, go ahead, order, she‚Äôs waiting.</p>
<p>‚ÄìCappuccino. What do you mean, cover stories?</p>
<p>‚ÄìQuisiera un espresso por favor. Every one of these quote benign technologies has a pretty easy to imagine military use. Laser <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/x-ray%20lithography" title="Wikipedia: x-ray lithography">x-ray lithography</a> for etching microchips, uh huh, right, and here‚Äôs one about kinder gentler <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical%20warfare" title="Wikipedia: Chemical warfare">C</a><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biological%20warfare" title="Wikipedia: Biological warfare">B</a>W, ‚Äúless virulent‚Äù tear gas for ‚Äúcrowd control‚Äù, heavier <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/specific%20gravity" title="Wikipedia: specific gravity">specific gravity</a> for controlled delivery, if this is the stuff you‚Äôre public about I can only imagine the rest.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôre wrong, there‚Äôs a genuine effort to convert to peacef</p>
<p>‚ÄìDual use, I know. Genuine effort to blur the line is what it is, and it goes far beyond the Lab, people in physics and comp sci departments across the country are lining up at the same trough, the grants are there and if they don‚Äôt take the money someone else will. That‚Äôs the reasoning. What a waste of talent and resources.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs more complicated than that. The people I work with, they‚Äôre not cynical.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, I know how people get caught up in their work. I have a friend there, not in Radiance, in another section. He‚Äôs a Quaker, he calls it ‚Äúbeing in the world‚Äù. At least he‚Äôs thought about it. How did you get into it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìMe? I‚Äôm, well, a lapsed theorist. But I‚Äôm not typical‚Ä¶ Was he not? R√©ti, Highet, Dietz, Thorpe, all had failed in some subtle way that in such a place could be denied. But where was there not failure and denial?</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo your people pay any attention at all to our demonstrations? [pg30]</p>
<p>‚ÄìIn J Section? Not much.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWe seem to bug your boss, at least.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHighet?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIn his little red sports car. What about you? What did you think about the big one yesterday?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt seemed, I don‚Äôt know, festive, almost a costume party, I didn‚Äôt realize at first it was Halloween‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut no, that wasn‚Äôt it. It was a ceremony. An exorcism.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh come on, what, you mean we‚Äôre possessed‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìBy arrogance, if nothing else.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs absurd, you can‚Äôt convince anyone with some absurd ritual‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs no different from your rituals, your bomb tests, just as absurd, but really dangerous!</p>
<p>‚ÄìThey‚Äôre not my tests‚Ä¶ and he remembered <em>B. Dietz &amp; P. Quine, sup.</em> ‚ÄìI‚Äôm sorry. I‚Äôm no good at talking about this.</p>
<p>The set of her features, so poised and eager, softened then and her voice lowered. ‚ÄìI don‚Äôt mean to attack you. I‚Äôm sure you think about it.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes but, but I‚Äôm not sure! What to do, I mean. What if it is a waste, what if, if all the money and the decades, all the lives and talent‚Ä¶ then it‚Äôs more than just me, it‚Äôs not just my mistake, but something wrong at the root of it, and what, what can I do about that?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIf it is a mistake, you can face it. You could stop.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut that wouldn‚Äôt stop anything. It‚Äôs almost as if these things we work on‚Ä¶ they use us to get born. Could use anyone.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt must be very hard for you. Their eyes met, and the troubled sympathy in hers wrung him. Her face was so concerned for him that he almost cried out with selfpity.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs not your fault. I, I need to get back now.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI really am sorry, can we‚Ä¶ can we forget about all this and just start over?</p>
<p>‚ÄìStart over‚Ä¶?</p>
<p>Abruptly he rose and walked away stolid with loathing of his own erratic heart, and of her for stirring it.</p>
<hr/>
<p>[pg31] In the night he woke sweating with a pulse of ninety, reached for the pillbottle next to the small box <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_LaBerge%23Lucid%20dreaming%20education%20and%20facilitation" title="Wikipedia: Stephen_LaBerge#Lucid dreaming education and facilitation">DREAMLIGHT</a> Unlock Your Inner Potential and its plastic headset. The pills opened a plain of timelessness in which it seemed a lost part of himself dwelled. as he lay in their haze, his fluency returned. Wonderful problems enticed and yielded to his insight, wisdom depended from the sky like fruit. He kept a notebook in case any insight survived his waking. None did.</p>
<p>He attached the headset like a blindfold. At the onset of dreaming a strobe would flicker there and rouse him enough to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucid%20dream" title="Wikipedia: Lucid dream">observe and direct his dream but not to wake</a>. He settled and conjured an image: the battle station shining in the void of space. Slender arms and rods pivoting. The missile rise in swarms, bright points on the black hollow of a crescent Earth. They blur in a silver mist of chaff. Above the crescent distant battle stations ignite in globes of light, their beams lance out, but swarm follows swarm up from the Earth, far too many to destroy. He pulled off the headset.</p>
<p>The world has changed, the old enemy has collapsed into ruined republics. Yet despite this consummation of all the Lab has strived for, the work goes on, the mood is spiritless, the shots in the desert continue like some ritual of penance, some black and endless propitiation of forces that in losing their fixed abode have grown closer and more menacing.</p>
<p>Stillness. Faint whistle of tinnitus, first sounds of birdcall. Wan dawn light. The enemy is gone. But the work goes on and on.<a href="#fn34" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref34"><sup>34</sup></a></p>
</section>
<section id="three" class="level3">
<h3>Three</h3>
<p>[pg32] For a while Lynn was not among the protesters. Their numbers had diminished to a small contingent by the main gate, holding a drooping sheet painted DIABOLIS EX MACHINA. Quine slowed through the gate and stopped, valves in the engine ticking, for a backhoe lurching across the main road, and closed his window against the dust billowing toward him as he went on past an air hammer breaking a sidewalk to rubble, overtones of its chatter following him across the rock moat and into the building where, too late to retreat, he saw Thorpe seated at Null‚Äôs computer tapping without letup at Quine‚Äôs entrance.</p>
<p>‚ÄìMorning, said Quine.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIs it? I‚Äôve been here all night. Something there for you to read.</p>
<p>On top of Quine‚Äôs stack of journals, a year‚Äôs unread accumulation, colored slips in their pages flagging articles that at an earlier time would not have waited a day, was a xerox topped with a yellow sticker SEEN THIS? <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical%20Review%20Letters" title="Wikipedia: Physical Review Letters">Physical Review Letters</a> 1954</em>. A dig at his age?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI know it‚Äôs old, said Thorpe. ‚ÄìBut I think it applies. See, I started with an EE from a hick school, taught myself quantum mechanics by reading Dirac, so my perspective is sort of, things don‚Äôt change that much. Lots of good ideas have been left hanging. That‚Äôs how I found your paper‚Ä¶ I mean‚Ä¶ stumbling at having touched as he thought Quine‚Äôs sensitive point, ‚Äìnot to say, it‚Äôs just, you know, if you‚Äôre a student like me, not well connected, not seeing all the latest preprints and hearing all the gossip, you need another way up. So this is my way, sort of looking for old forgotten stuff to build on. [pg3]</p>
<p>‚ÄìSo tell me about this.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI came across it working for Fish and Himmelhoch, looking for a sort of nuclear model to explain the cold fusion reaction? Okay I know, the current wisdom is, there‚Äôs no reaction, it‚Äôs bogus, or if anything is happening it‚Äôs electrochemical, okay, fine. But you know, if you model the process in a nuclear way, it looks like a phenomenon called <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/super-radiance" title="Wikipedia: super-radiance">super-radiance</a>. The equations are similar. Highet saw the connection.</p>
<p>‚ÄìTo this? Highet told you about Superbright?</p>
<p>‚ÄìVery sharp guy.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs quite a breach of classification.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHe sort of hinted around it, citing the open literature. Anyway it‚Äôs moot, I‚Äôm cleared now. What do you think?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôll read it when I get a chance, dropping it back on to the stack of journals.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut, I mean, we don‚Äôt have much time. Should I pursue it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat have you been doing?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell, here, let me show you, I started sort of modifying your code but I had a couple of quest</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou changed my files?</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo no I made copies, changes only on my copies and I</p>
