<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôll work with him, but I don‚Äôt have to like him or share office space with him. It‚Äôs bad enough Null‚Äôs stuff is still there.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThorpe has his own space. You want him out, you can tell him so. By the way, R√©ti‚Äôs here for a visit, you might want to pay your respects. Instead of running around down in Fabrication with Dietz.</p>
<p>‚ÄìSomeone has to tend to those details.</p>
<p>‚ÄìLet me tell you something, Philip, I‚Äôm a smart guy but to be brutally honest I‚Äôm a second rate physicist. I have the ideas but not the persistence, I‚Äôve known that about myself for twenty years. But I‚Äôve learned to position myself and to use other people to get what I want. Win win, you know, we help each other look good. You take my point?</p>
<p>Voices approach in the corridor as Highet went on in a lower tone, ‚ÄìOne path in the world is up. There‚Äôs also a path down. What there isn‚Äôt is standing still.<a href="#fn36" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref36"><sup>36</sup></a> Now you, friend, have been standing still [pg36] for quite a little while. I‚Äôd say you need to make some career decisions soon, before they‚Äôre made for you.</p>
<p>Flanked by two Lab factotums, Aron R√©ti came slowly, stamping his cane, into Highet‚Äôs office. His eyes, azure behind thick lenses, peered without recognition as Quine greeted him. ‚ÄìAh, my young friend, how are you?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou remember Philip Quine, Aron. That beautifully sweet photon detector he built for us.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOf course, of course.</p>
