<hr/>
<p>As night came on the life of the building went to X Section, the Playpen, where the younger men worked on schemes even more speculative than Superbright, and Quine returned for the thousandth time to his simulation with the sinking heart of a man returning to a loveless home. Entrapment. As if fine wire had threaded his drugged veins, and now, as feeling returned, any movement might tear him open. He fidgeted the radio on to, ‚Äìfades to a reddish color as it enters Earth‚Äôs shad, and off as he saw again the tilt of Nan‚Äôs head, the fine whorls of her ear, the man‚Äôs dark hand cupping her neck. The ridge of her collarbone, the warm pulse of the vein across it.</p>
<p>On Null‚Äôs whiteboard deltas sigmas omegas integrals infinities in variegated ink still wove like fundamental forces their elegant pattern around a void. From the clutter on the desk he lifted CENTURY 21 LAB QUARTERLY. Changing world betokens larger role for science. Acceptable levels of social risk. Public does not fully understand. World free of threats too much to ask. Revolutionary new technique. Major improvement. Important to a variety of national goals. Unique multi-disciplinary expertise. Two young men, one poised to hurl a balloon, caromed past his doorway. He shut the door on guffaws and ‚Äìteach you some hydrodynamics!</p>
<p>He picked up Black 1954. He looked at the citations, then read from the start. He stopped often to reread, with a doggedness that made shift for his halt sense, once so fine, of the rhythms of scientific thought, the probe and test and parry and clinch that now required his slow and remedial attention to be grasped. As he read, his respect for Thorpe grew even as an emptiness opened with him. When he was finished he started into space before reaching across the desk to snap off the lights.</p>
<p>The phone chattered. On the second ring he lifted it, holding [pg39] silence to ear for a moment before speaking. In the darkness the computer screen, phosphors charged by the room‚Äôs vanished light, was a dim fading square.</p>
<p>‚ÄìQuine.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHi, it‚Äôs Lynn, I‚Äôm glad I caught you. I‚Äôm hiking up Mount Ohlone with some friends tonight, you want to come?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìI know it‚Äôs short notice.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI should be working.</p>
<p>‚ÄìGood heavens, all night? We‚Äôre not starting till nine.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo but‚Ä¶ He scrutinized the whiteboard as if this quandary might be expressed there in double integrals. ‚ÄìI mean‚Ä¶ sure, why not.</p>
<p>‚ÄìGood! Meet us at the park gate. It‚Äôs ten miles north on Crow Canyon Road.</p>
<p>In the hallway a length of surgical tubing, knotted at both ends, lay ruptured and limp in a film of water. As he left the building sprinklers came on in a silver mist and rainbows shimmered in the floodlit air. He drove out past parked vehicles and armed men in fatigues.</p>
<p>He arrived early. The sky was starry, the moon full. Some planet was setting in the west, probably Saturn by its color. The V of Taurus pointed back the way he‚Äôd come. A car approached, lights snagging in the trees, then came around the last bend lightless and rolled to a stop.</p>
<p>‚ÄìMark, Julie, this is Philip.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhy‚Äôre we whispering?</p>
<p>‚ÄìPark‚Äôs closed. Not supposed to be here.</p>
<p>They went around the closed gate and past a building set back among trees. In a second story window a dim line flickered, a fluorescent tube not on nor off, stuttering between states. Fifty yards further they left the road for a broad path that rose winding under black oak, then bay. An owl called, leaving the harbor of a eucalyptus.</p>
<p>Quine and Lynn walked in silence. Ahead Julie laughed and touched Mark‚Äôs arm, not a lover‚Äôs touch, but a gesture of intimacy with the world, the same hand caressing air and underbrush. They talked about people they knew, hes and shes darting in and out of audibility like moths in the dark. Soon they entered a darkness of [pg40] trees where nothing was visible but shards of the moon fallen like leaves around them. He went more slowly and stumbled. Lynn paused and he heard a rustling. Leaves popped free of a branch and came crushed under Quine‚Äôs nose, carrying to him a strong waft of mint and resin.</p>
<p>‚ÄìSweet bay, she said, ‚Äìis sacred to Apollo, but this is not <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bay%20Laurel" title="Wikipedia: Bay Laurel">European bay</a>, <em>Laurens</em>, it‚Äôs California bay, <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umbellularia" title="Wikipedia: Umbellularia">Umbellularia</a></em>. Her tongue lingered on the liquids.</p>
<p>They kept climbing until they broke from the woods into an open slope. Moonlight rinsed palely the open range land below them.</p>
<p>‚Äì<em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artemisia%20tridentata" title="Wikipedia: Artemisia tridentata">Artemisia tridentata</a></em>, Lynn said, inhaling as she broke from a sagebrush a twig of gray leaves.</p>
<p>It was pungent in her cupped palm. The warmth of her came with it.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNamed for the goddess Artemis. Who loves it. And this is willow. <em>Salix</em>. <em>Los alamos</em>. Which is the meaning of Orpheus‚Äôs name. Who opened doors he couldn‚Äôt reenter.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHow do you know all this?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThis is where I grew up. This is the smell of my home. This is how I know I belong.</p>
<p>They came up to Mark and Julie at the edge of the grove. The moon hung above them, swollen, no goddess remontant but an airless world already mapped, trodden, and projected for division into satrapies of mining, manufacturing, and defense, occupancy deferred only until these scenarios could enrich their planners at a margin of return greater and more reliable than what current technology assured.</p>
<p>‚ÄìLet‚Äôs sit here.</p>
<p>Julie passed around bread, cheese, fruit, a plastic bottle of water. On the grass they sat eating. Somewhere crickets chirred on and off, their presence like a field of energy shifting.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs so warm tonight. Almost like summer.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou from around here, Philip?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI went to school in the East. I‚Äôve been working around here for eight years.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPractically a native. What do you do?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI write software. [pg41]</p>
<p>‚ÄìFriend of mine works for CodeWin, maybe you know him.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs a big industry.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBigger by the day, said Lynn dryly.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhere‚Äôs the Big Dipper? I can‚Äôt see it, said Julie, standing.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs too low to see, said Quine. ‚ÄìThat‚Äôs the handle above the ridgeline. There in the west, that‚Äôs Vega setting. A summer star. Winter coming in over there‚Ä¶ pointing to that swarm of fireflies tangled in a silver braid, ‚ÄìThe Pleiades. Also called the Seven Sisters. You can count more than seven on a clear night. But not with the moon out. And right behind them Orion, you can see him just coming over the horizon, those three stars in a line. Chasing them. Kind of a bad luck bunch, the Sisters. They were all seduced by one god or another, except for Merope, who married Sisyphus.</p>
<p>‚ÄìLook! Is that a planet?</p>
<p>Finding the pale green disk where Julie pointed, a handsbreath from the Sisters, Quine knew it was the beam of a laser ten miles south stabbing to the edge of space where sodium atoms glowed in its heat.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo, not a planet‚Ä¶ Suddenly Lynn‚Äôs hand was in his. She squeezed it once, and before he could respond released it to run downhill toward a dark grove. He stood for a moment and then he ran too. He ran for no reason he could name, wind in his ears, an excitement rising almost to fear in his heart, hackles alive. Some presence almost, chasing him. Then the darkness of the trees was around him and he tripped and went sprawling. The presence was still there. He feared it though he knew it was benign. It was not death, but it would change his life if he let it.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip? Are you all right?</p>
<p>She stood over him, at the edge of the grove as Mark and Julie approached. He lay there in anxiety, anger almost at how she‚Äôd stirred him, at the beauty of her movement, at the way her features held the moonlight.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip‚Ä¶?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm fine. He brushed leaf dirt from his sleeves. The presence was gone. They walked in silence until emerging from the grove and heading downslope. Overhead the green star had vanished.</p>
<p>‚ÄìSo what are you working on now, Philip? [pg42]</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh‚Ä¶ things in the sky, Quine said. ‚ÄìAn aerospace partner wants us to program low orbit balloons a couple of miles across, the apparent size of the moon, sunlit, carrying messages, logos, advertising‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut that‚Äôs so, Julie began and Mark cut in, ‚ÄìSeems I read about this. The Sierra Club‚Äôs bringing suit, aren‚Äôt they?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt know about that, we‚Äôre just the contractors, I just do my job‚Ä¶ and Julie glancing at Lynn claimed Mark‚Äôs arm to move them away and resume in a low voice their conversation of hes and shes while Lynn walked apart, obliging Quine to follow, leaving behind ‚Äìshe sees him as a reclamation project‚Ä¶ to overtake her on a knoll. She waited with crossed arms. Behind her, the valley was filled with glittering points. At its far verge was the floodlit terrain of the Lab.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip, what are you doing?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou don‚Äôt like me as a software mogul?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIs that your, your cover story? Her face remained still and fixed on him, moonshadow in her eyes‚Äô hollows.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat balloon thing really is a Lab project, they started a small group on it‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou don‚Äôt want to tell them what you really do.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo, I‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou think Mark isn‚Äôt smart enough to see through you? He is. You take his good faith for foolishness.</p>
<p>‚ÄìLook I, I just didn‚Äôt know what you told them. I didn‚Äôt want you to be embarrassed by me. His face heated as he said it.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell, that would be my problem, wouldn‚Äôt it. Now I have a different problem. Because it happens I did tell them. She waited for something he wasn‚Äôt able to give her, then went on. ‚ÄìWhen you were talking about the Pleiades you were so, I don‚Äôt know, at ease. What happened?</p>
<p>‚ÄìLook, I‚Äôm sorry, I just‚Ä¶ Another breath of warm breeze and he realized he was sweating.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat happened?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat green star we saw. It wasn‚Äôt a star, it was something from the Lab. A laser test.</p>
<p>‚ÄìA Radiance laser? [pg43]</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo‚Ä¶ something else. Unclassified. A guide star for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/adaptive%20optics" title="Wikipedia: adaptive optics">adaptive optics</a>.<a href="#fn37" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref37"><sup>37</sup></a></p>
<p>She was listening with her arms still crossed. ‚ÄìWhy did that change your mood?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs just, I‚Äôd almost forgotten, about everything except, except for being here. That thing in the sky reminded me. Then Mark asked what I did‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìThey really have their hooks in you, don‚Äôt they.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI know that.</p>
<p>Face still hollowed in moonshadow she stepped toward him. His need to be touched and take comfort welled up, but some structure unknown yet dreadful held him still. After a moment‚Äôs wait she turned to face the valley lights. ‚ÄìI‚Äôm surprised you haven‚Äôt quit.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAnd do what! Turn from the one place where my, my talents have some use?</p>
