<p>‚ÄìThey haven‚Äôt robbed you of that.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, that‚Äôs so, I gave myself over, and now I‚Äôm on the line for something I don‚Äôt care about. That‚Äôs the way, yes, you‚Äôre going to get screwed regardless, so you should make sure it‚Äôs for something that matters to you‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat would that be?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt know.</p>
<p>Julie and Mark were calling. They went down the slope and rejoined them. She was still talking to Mark, ‚Äìso I‚Äôm, wait, stop, this is it, these are the boundaries and he‚Äôs like, what did I do? She turned to Lynn with the pack, ‚Äìtake this? and embraced Mark from behind, arms around his chest, straps of her shortlegged overalls a dark X on her back, bare calves duckwalking the pair down the slope.</p>
<p>In the lot Lynn said to Julie, ‚ÄìGet a ride with you guys?</p>
<p>Quine called out, ‚ÄìMark, just joking about the balloon.</p>
<p>Mark looked up, fumbling with his keys, smiling. ‚ÄìOh yeah?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThanks, thanks for, for inviting me. He got in the car, opened the glovebox, found a tablet, brushed lint from it, swallowed it dry. [pg44]</p>
<hr/>
<p>In his apartment was a smell like stale smoke and old sweat and rotting food, edged with something fouler, like the metallic stench of the flux from the open pipe. At first he thought it came from outside, where earlier they‚Äôd been roofing. But on the deck the air was fresh. He knelt to the carpet and smelled nothing. In the kitchen he bent to the drain and smelled nothing. From a bottle he squeezed a pearl of soap onto a sponge, ran hot water in the sink, scrubbed and rinsed it. He scrubbed the stove top. The ceiling fan was silted over by grease and spiderweb. He fetched a chair and reached to touch it. A black gobbet fell from it to the stove top. He fetched pliers and freed the nuts holding the shield, banging with the handle to break the dried paint around the rim. In both hands he bore the shield like a chalice to the sink.</p>
<p>In its concavities had pooled a glossy tar. He scrubbed it for minutes, smutch washing into the sink. Then he spooled off yards of paper toweling, wet and soaped it, and climbed the chair to wash over and again the sleeve of the fan, the blades, the hub. A viscous brown residue clung to the towels and his fingers. Further into the recess, beyond his reach, was more tar.</p>
<p>Sweat soaked him. He went onto the deck. The moon was dim and reddish, as if the sky held smoke. He stared in wonder and fear until the knowledge that it was an eclipse broke upon him banishing fear and wonder alike.</p>
<p>When he went back in the smell was waiting. He understood that from now on everything would smell like this. For a while he sat at the table with his eyes shut, then opened the newspaper for the memory of CARPETS CLEANED but it parted to 24 HRS OUTCALL DAWNA and LOVE TALK $2/MIN and he stared bleakly at the sullen pout, circleted forehead, hair as wild as if fresh risen from the sea, linen garb pleated in most subtle fashion. His hand found the telephone, and after a distant chirrup a small insinuating voice flicked like a tongue in his ear, and he stepped back from the uncradled receiver, switched off the lights, leaving the voice breathing unheeded into the darkness and the moonlight pooled on the floor.</p>
<p>He showered. In the stream lust swelled in him like nausea. Hot [pg45] spray lashed him. Incoherent images flashed upon him. Runnels nudged moonwhite globs toward the drain. Depleted he toweled. On the sink were Nan‚Äôs toothpaste, hairbrush, lipstick, mascara. On the toilet tank an unzipped travel kit of quilted cotton gaped to show diaphragm, jelly, tampons, vitamins, ibuprofen, hairpins, barrette, lens wetter, a glass jar of face cream. A towelend snagged in the zipper as Quine scrubbed dry his hair, dragging the kit. Items hailed on the tile floor. He dropped the towel, then swept his hand across the sink top. He grabbed the kit and hurled it. The jar flew out and smashed against the wall. [pg46]</p>
</section>
<section id="four" class="level3">
<h3>Four</h3>
<p>Dry sycamore leaves scraped over pavement in a hot wind drawn out from distant desert by a stalled offshore low. Over the ridge east of town dust and the smell of manure from the farmlands and a haze of smoke blew fitfully into the valley. as the sun rose through layers of haze Quine, driving to the back gate of the Lab so as to avoid the protesters, passed the dead vineyard by the north boundary. He pulled over, stilling the engine and the radio‚Äôs ‚Äìty thousand acres ablaze.</p>
<p>The gate was closed but unlocked. A bright new sign bore the bio-hazard trefoil and DANGER TOXICS MITIGATION PILOT SITE ALPHA KEEP OUT. The drone of flies rose and fell like a turbine. Stunted vines clung to irrigation uprights. Bark from one sloughed like ash on his fingers. From deep in the vineyard a warm moist flatus perfused the air. A stink like the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/chyme" title="Wikipedia: chyme">chyme</a> of a dying beast. He ran back to the car choking and drooling. At an irrigation faucet he rinsed his mouth, his face, his hair, his hands, yet the foulness, as of corroded metal, lingered. What god loves this?</p>
<p>At Null‚Äôs desk Thorpe worked.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBernd Dietz called. He has to know where to put the reflectors.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm tempted to leave them where they were in the last shot.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWe can‚Äôt do that, Highet would</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs why I‚Äôm tempted.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYeah he‚Äôs, he can be a real prick can‚Äôt he.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNot if you play by his rules. He always has a carrot handy.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell I have quite a few ideas but you need to look them over, sort [pg47] of tell me where they‚Äôre out of line, you know we‚Äôre really down to the wire here and</p>
<p>‚ÄìOkay, let‚Äôs assume Black‚Äôs right‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh then you‚Äôve read</p>
<p>‚ÄìAssume we‚Äôre looking at quanta as localized particles guided by a physically real field‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìHighet, you know he really grilled me on this stuff when he came out to Utah, put me through the wringer, made me prove every assumption, but after an hour I had him convinced, and I thought he really respected‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìTypical Highet slap and stroke.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNow suppose we‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôre good at this. And very fast.</p>
<p>‚ÄìCommercial software you know, those eighteen hour days tone you right up.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo don‚Äôt touch that, we can‚Äôt change the rod array, I‚Äôve already told Dietz.</p>
<p>‚ÄìCan we reorient it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìMaybe. I‚Äôll check.</p>
<p>Under Thorpe‚Äôs shaping the model gradually began to show correlation. After several hours one run produced an annulus. Then nothing for hours more. Again the annulus. He rotated the model‚Äôs rods again and again and at one angle power jumped and the annulus closed to a point. They stared at the screen. Thorpe bit his thumb. ‚ÄìWhat do you think?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt looks all right.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt looks fantastic. It‚Äôs a hundred times brighter than the last shot. But the model‚Äôs tweaked to hell and gone.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt see anything wrong.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo, neither do I. So now if we put the reflectors here‚Ä¶ see, this is how I work. I‚Äôm not a theorist, I don‚Äôt have your background, I need to, you know, immerse myself in the code, feel the system‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell, it‚Äôs a remarkable job. I couldn‚Äôt have done this. I‚Äôve tried for months.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell, I couldn‚Äôt have done it if your code wasn‚Äôt so comprehensive [pg48]. You really worked at this. But it‚Äôs, you know, at some level it‚Äôs all just sort of pushing numbers around. I don‚Äôt know if it‚Äôs saying anything real.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWe‚Äôll know soon enough.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you think something‚Äôs wrong?</p>
<p>Quine shrugged. ‚ÄìNothing I can see.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôre not convinced.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt have to be. It‚Äôs what Highet wants, isn‚Äôt it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYeah but, that‚Äôs not what you think I‚Äôm doing, is it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìBecause I would never do that.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm sure you</p>
<p>‚ÄìSince the Fish and Himmelhoch thing I have to be very careful. They were crucified, just crucified, they‚Äôre pariahs, their careers are finished. Anything remotely to do with cold fusion is tainted, you may as well say you‚Äôre working on perpetual motion. And I was on that team, I was in that lab. So I have to be very careful.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPerpetual motion, you could probably sell that to Highet. At least as a talking point.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs not funny to me. I had nothing to do with that debacle, just so we‚Äôre clear on that.</p>
<p>‚ÄìSure. I understand.</p>
<p>‚ÄìSorry I‚Äôm touchy. Just, you know, tired. You‚Äôve been generous, letting me work with your code and all, I really thought you‚Äôd stick me with the scut work but you‚Äôve done it haven‚Äôt you, all the test details, and let me do the interesting part. This could take me a long way and I‚Äôm grateful.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhy don‚Äôt you go home, get some sleep?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYeah, okay, I‚Äôm whipped.</p>
<p>‚ÄìTake tomorrow off. I‚Äôll tell Highet.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo no, I‚Äôll be in. We have to write up a work order.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôll do it, don‚Äôt worry about it.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAre you staying?</p>
<p>‚ÄìGod no, what is it, midnight?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs, oh Jesus, it‚Äôs two a m.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo, I‚Äôm leaving in five minutes. I‚Äôll write the work order tomorrow. [pg49]</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh I meant to, here‚Äôs something else for you to read‚Ä¶ and, hesitating a moment, Thorpe placed a stapled xerox on Quine‚Äôs stack, held his gaze for a moment, and departed.</p>
<p>It was a new paper by Sorokin. At <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CERN" title="Wikipedia: CERN">CERN</a> now. Quine skimmed it as if reading news from a distant galaxy or a remote epoch. It solidified and extended the work they‚Äôd done together, the experiment that had separated them. It was clear that it was a field now, and that Sorokin owned it. He stanched an upwelling of envy and selfpity.</p>
<p>But instead of going home Quine broke apart Thorpe‚Äôs code and studied the changes. He gave the model a new set of energies: points clustered around the focus. Again, with different energies, the same focus emerged. Something was wrong, he could smell it; his instinct was not yet dead.</p>
<p>Near dawn he found it. Along with the sensor positions, Thorpe had tweaked the sensor response function. Playing the system, as he said, to get results. But now the function emphasized certain wavelengths. As might the sensors themselves when struck by the bomb‚Äôs radiation. The brightness from the earlier tests might be nothing but reflection, instrument error. When you put that error into the focusing code, the code naturally confirmed the data. Glue in a house of cards. And down in a corner of Null‚Äôs whiteboard, half erased, was it? yes, the same function, the same tweak. There in the corner of his eye for months. Wasted months. Wrong from the start. Error or fraud? No way to know. Maybe started as one, became the other. But wait now. If you removed the tweak, if you stopped trying for a beam, chaff fell from the problem and the expressions said something else entirely.</p>
<p>A presence entered the room. Air gravid and light adance. There appeared to his mind‚Äôs eye the battle station lost and insignificant in a tide of radiance, all the universe‚Äôs light at wavelengths and colors beyond mere vision, streaming in intricate brocade, weaving and mediating between matter and energy, wave and particle, the phenomenal and the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/noumenal" title="Wikipedia: noumenal">noumenal</a>. Here was the mystery, at last, open for his knowing as he hovered between fatigue and ecstasy, and he knew he was unready to pass through the gate of revelation into this realm of light. He drew back. And the presence like a roebuck in forest startled [pg50] and was gone. The tide of light receded. He was left with only the particulars of rods and reflectors. But he had found their flaw. Mystery might elude, but the information was sure. Thus angels must feel, radiant with the certainty that flows from their single devotion to right.</p>
<hr/>
<p>‚ÄìBernd, I need some reflectors.</p>
<p>‚ÄìFor Taliesin.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI know, I have a work order already, this morning, from Thorpe.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo, I need more.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWe do not have time to add</p>
<p>‚ÄìI have to have reflectors made of something other than beryllium.</p>
<p>Dietz was silent. He began leafing through a logbook. ‚ÄìDo you know, try as we might we cannot keep traces of oxygen out of the beryllium. I have told Highet this. Long ago.</p>
<p>‚ÄìReally.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI have proposed hydrogen in the past.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhy haven‚Äôt we tried it?</p>
<p>‚Äì‚ÄúDon‚Äôt mess with success.‚Äù</p>
<p>‚ÄìI see. I‚Äôd like to try it.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDoes Highet approve?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôll take responsibility.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWithout his approval I can do nothing.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBernd. This is what Slater thought, isn‚Äôt it. That the beryllium reflectors were giving false brightness. And Null knew it too, didn‚Äôt he.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI did not see Slater‚Äôs report. Dietz did not look up from the book.</p>
<p>‚ÄìMake some hydrogen reflectors for me. Cable them separately from the beryllium.</p>
<p>Dietz shut the book. ‚ÄìSend me a work order. I will have to send a copy to Highet.</p>
<p>Kihara came through the doors with a following of suited men.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWon‚Äôt be a minute gentlemen, don‚Äôt let us disturb you, you can see here the precision engineering we‚Äôre capable of, bang-up job of inventiveness, maximum return on investment, the answer to reversing the balance of trade deficit, innovative federally generated <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/technology%20transfer" title="Wikipedia: technology transfer">technology transfer</a> to industry, improves the nation‚Äôs economic competitiveness [pg51] as we work deliberately and consciously to build partnerships, a new class of information with commercial value, very creative cooperative efforts, freedom to negotiate intellectual property rights, fees and royalties, cover the technological waterfront, take for instance these fine-grained <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/superplastic" title="Wikipedia: superplastic">superplastic</a> steels, not to mention <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/x-ray%20lithography" title="Wikipedia: x-ray lithography">x-ray lithography</a>‚Ä¶ and Quine returned to his office rummaging through CENTURY 21, Rings Fields and Groups, Computer Addict Wholesale Microcenter, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TeX" title="Wikipedia: TeX">TeX</a> Technical Reference, to come upon WORK ORDER Form 4439A Authorized Use Only, and sat for a minute holding a pen above it suddenly frozen at the sound of Thorpe‚Äôs approaching voice, ‚Äìyou have to invoke the world control option from the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/command%20line" title="Wikipedia: command line">command line</a>, relaxing as the voice receded, pen moving to spell SECONDARY SENSOR ARRAY.</p>
<hr/>
<p>From Highet‚Äôs open door he heard, ‚ÄìYou want less pressure, try the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute%20for%20Advanced%20Study" title="Wikipedia: Institute for Advanced Study">Institute for Advanced Salaries</a><a href="#fn38" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref38"><sup>38</sup></a>, it‚Äôs a fucking retirement village for the reality-impaired! and a lower voice unintelligible in response, then ‚ÄìI don‚Äôt care, I want results! the lower voice growing sharper, ‚Äìis cheap. My people have to make it happen, as the door opened and Dietz, pale and shaking, came out past Quine glancing at him without a word and stormed down the hall, Highet following to the door, calling out, ‚ÄìA beard without a mustache, does that make you an honest man? and to Quine, ‚ÄìYou. I don‚Äôt want to talk to you now. Send me e-mail.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI think you‚Äôll want to hear this. We can show quantitative agreement.</p>
<p>Highet looked at him with loathing. ‚ÄìYou want to change the reflectors. The day before the shot.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI want to try hydrogen.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs an incredibly bad idea, that‚Äôs totally braindead<a href="#fn39" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref39"><sup>39</sup></a>, to introduce a new measurement technique at this stage. You have to calibrate, you have to</p>
<p>‚ÄìIf Slater‚Äôs right, if the beryllium shows false brightness, it‚Äôs only a matter of time until we know it. It might as well be now. Or do you want to spend another fifty million on another shot?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôd love to. Who told you Slater said that?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs common knowledge. We‚Äôll have to address the issue eventually. [pg52]</p>
<p>‚ÄìCommon knowledge my ass.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThen it might be wise to preempt questions about it. The shot‚Äôs so close to the presentation, we can‚Äôt be expected to have data that quickly. But we could say we‚Äôre investigating. If we have to.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôre sure about the quantitative agreement?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe simulation‚Äôs excellent. I won‚Äôt take credit for it. Jef Thorpe did the work.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDid he now. Well, we‚Äôre a team. Good results show good management.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôd like Jef to give the presentation.</p>
<p>Highet‚Äôs eyes fixed in calculation on Quine as the phone rang and Quine waited for the dismissive wave with which Highet ended audiences, but instead he spoke a moment, then covered the mouthpiece and said, ‚ÄìWant to make some money Philip, Devon Null‚Äôs taking on investors, and uncovering the mouthpiece, ‚ÄìYes, application‚Äôs outside the envelope no problem there, keep me briefed, and in another moment hung up, leaning back and clasping his hands over his thinning crown, gazing at the ceiling.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell that‚Äôs fine, that‚Äôs very fine. Wonder if we could work up a little something. I could invite some key people to the ranch for the shot, some unnamed sources, goose the process a little, can we get Thorpe in on this?</p>
<p>‚ÄìHe‚Äôs probably in my office.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou may work out yet Philip, Highet grudged as one thick finger stabbed the phone. ‚ÄìJef? Leo. Get over here, rising to pace past framed and signed photos of three Presidents, another of R√©ti and himself with the current President, artist‚Äôs rendering of the Superbright and of a fusion driven spaceship, cartoon of a mushroom cloud WHEN YOU CARE ENOUGH TO SEND THE VERY BEST, certificates from professional societies, a length of cable, a circuit board. He stopped at the window, gaze caught by something, and parted the vertical slats of the blind with his fingers, speaking softly, almost to himself.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you know the darkness that‚Äôs out there? Do you realize how tenuous this all is? Twenty thousand years of civilization, and only in the last few hundred has rationality begun to displace superstition. I tell you I would sup with the devil, I would risk armageddon, not to [pg53] lose that. When I think of those fucking tree huggers out there‚Ä¶ and turning back to Quine, voice low and insistent, ‚ÄìThink the ills are in a system, think it‚Äôs that simple, R√©ti and his anticommunism, your new girlfriend and her peacenik buddies, wonder why‚Äôs she drawn to you?</p>
<p>‚ÄìNow wait just a</p>
<p>‚ÄìDarkness and malady is in the human heart, Philip, don‚Äôt you know that? The enemy is the heart. You can‚Äôt hide from that darkness‚Ä¶ as Thorpe entered in black linen jacket, red t-shirt, nose stud, eyes eager, and Highet‚Äôs demeanor switched to the cheerful, ‚ÄìJef, my man. I want to wow the rubes when we go to the desert. We have a ranch out there with <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digital%20Signal%203" title="Wikipedia: Digital Signal 3">T3</a> data lines from the test site. What can you do that‚Äôs portable and fantastic? I want flash that makes you reach for your checkbook.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôve got an interface toolkit from my CodeWin days, I can throw something together. Just tell me what kind of data I have to work with.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôll email you the details. Shot‚Äôs tomorrow evening, not too much for you, is it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìDemo or die, I know the drill, said Thorpe, grinning.</p>
<hr/>
<p>The evening wind whipped dust across the highway, vibrating the cars stopped in three lanes behind flashing lights at Codornic s EXIT NLY as Quine punched ‚Äìillion in property loss, over to ‚Äìnoninjury accident being cleared at the Codornices Road exit not blocking lanes for you, drowned in a siren blaring up the shoulder OHLONE VALLEY RESCUE ∆é∆Ü–òA‚ÖÉU·ô†MA as Quine edged against horns and unheard curses into the exit lane and cut back onto a commercial strip behind the central mall, the reverse of which colonnaded and pedimented facade, its raw concrete stained by rains, caught with a sort of wounded dignity the sun‚Äôs last rays as they likewise gilded Estancia Estates An Adult Community where Quine parked and for a moment held in his gaze a prospect of identical bungalows arrayed on lawns billiard-green out to the surveyed boundaries of chainlink and dry pasture beyond.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh! Philip. Come in. I wasn‚Äôt expecting you, your deadline‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell it‚Äôs Friday night, I thought</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm glad you, but, if you‚Äôd called I would have made dinner‚Ä¶ [pg54]</p>
<p>‚ÄìI wasn‚Äôt sure I was coming.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYour work is done?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThere‚Äôs a test. I fly out tomorrow afternoon. And there‚Äôs a presentation Monday.</p>
<p>‚ÄìCan you stay tonight? We can go out for‚Ä¶ is something wrong?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI need to ask you something.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes? What is it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWho‚Äôs the guy with the curly black hair and the good tan?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe, what?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI happened to see you the other day. In a hallway. He was acting kind of proprietary.</p>
<p>‚ÄìProprie, her face flushed and she turned to look across the room, one hand resting on a table. Quine waited.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHow long has this been going on?</p>
<p>‚ÄìHis name‚Äôs Ben and he‚Äôs a good friend, and it‚Äôs been, we‚Äôve been friends for years. Since before I knew you.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou still see him?</p>
<p>The flush darkened, and as she turned back to him her mild features contorted into a stiff anger he‚Äôd never seen in her. ‚ÄìDo you mean, do I sleep with him? Yes. I have. Once or twice since you and I have been together.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOnce or twice. You‚Äôve lost count.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh, Philip! Why are you, this is hateful!</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt hurts me, Nan.</p>
<p>Her face was a mask of plain misery. ‚ÄìWe never</p>
<p>‚ÄìNever what, laid down rules? I didn‚Äôt think we had to, I thought some things went without saying.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWithout saying what! That I‚Äôm yours alone when you don‚Äôt give me anything, for God‚Äôs sake Philip I didn‚Äôt turn to Ben for sex, just for, for kindness, for friendship, just to feel that I mattered! To someone! Five years of my life Philip, I‚Äôm no longer a young woman, do you want to know when it was I saw Ben, when I went to him after you and I were together?</p>
<p>The coldness, the absolute coldness of the moment.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou don‚Äôt, you don‚Äôt even care do you. It hurts you, but I can see in your eyes, you won‚Äôt listen to me. How can I possibly explain when [pg55] you won‚Äôt even give me credit for, for loving you, Philip? When you and I met, at that picnic, and I was so charmed by you, by your intelligence, your modesty, your reserve. Do you remember, the thunderstorm? I hadn‚Äôt seen one since moving West. And afterwards you took me home, we were drenched, and I loaned you clothes. Oh Philip, it was long over between Ben and me, he was like a brother, I just wanted to say goodbye, to tell someone close to me how happy I was. How happy I thought I‚Äôd be.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAnd the second time?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, that‚Äôs all you want to hear. Two years later, when you didn‚Äôt come to dinner, didn‚Äôt call, and I waited and waited, so it was only an anniversary just a date on the calendar that‚Äôs all, but I called Ben and he came over to be with me, and he didn‚Äôt, didn‚Äôt even want‚Ä¶ cut off by her sobs.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut I, you know I was working, you could have</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhen you come here and, and sulk for hours, barely acknowledge my existence, don‚Äôt call for days on end, then expect, how do you think that makes me feel‚Ä¶ I would have told you about Ben if you‚Äôd asked if you‚Äôd ever shown any interest at all. If you even know who I am!</p>
<p>Within him a stone fell and fell, soundlessly turning.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip, talk to me! Don‚Äôt turn away like this!</p>
<p>‚ÄìI have nothing to say, and he was out the door, where streetlights had come on, knowing that his leaving now was worse than anything gone before, a withdrawal he could never make right. Don‚Äôt tell me, don‚Äôt tell me we don‚Äôt feed the emptiness in each other. [pg56]</p>
</section>
<section id="five" class="level3">
<h3>Five</h3>
<p>In the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great%20Basin" title="Wikipedia: Great Basin">Great Basin</a> of Nevada thousands of acres of waste and infecund desert had been reclaimed for science as the Aguas Secas Weapons Test Site<a href="#fn40" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref40"><sup>40</sup></a>, and one hundred miles further west was the Advanced Research Institute of the Eastern Sierra, a ranch at the edge of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Owens%20Valley" title="Wikipedia: Owens Valley">Owens Valley</a>, a black facility whose funding appeared in no budget. Leased to the government by a conservative businessman, it served as a layover site for Lab personnel on their way to the desert. It nestled in the broad base of a canyon near a creek‚Äôs loud runoff through lateral <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/moraine" title="Wikipedia: moraine">moraine</a>. To the west the ground rose in the space of a few miles from six thousand feet to a twelve thousand foot crest of granite crags. Below, a few miles to the east, the north-south highway lay like a dropped ribbon across the wrinkled valley floor, and a hundred miles further across desert dotted with sage under a flotilla of thunderheads was the chalk white sink of Aguas Secas.</p>
<p>Even before joining the Lab Quine had seen ARIES. On his first trip west, while switching planes at Phoenix, he‚Äôd been paged and diverted to a single engine craft bound for a Kern County airstrip, where a sheriff‚Äôs four by four awaited him. The first Radiance shot had just gone off and at the ranch they were celebrating. Quine met Highet there. Highet was beating a twelve year old at chess, telling the boy, I‚Äôll trade a bishop for a knight anytime, I love knights, they leap barriers, they face eight ways at once.</p>
<p>A month later Quine was at Aguas. Rank smell of sage hovered in the predawn cool, immensities of desert air quivered to the horizon. [pg57] They drove with the sun rising behind them, the young initiates joking, group leaders and guards and observers in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Department%20of%20Defense" title="Wikipedia: Department of Defense">DoD</a> hardhats silent and grim. Roadways of cables led from instrument trailers over desert pocked with the collapse craters of previous tests to the distant borehole. Above it a red crane pointed straight up. The count reached zero. And the earth rippled. A wave rushed toward them and the ground shook as if a train were passing and passing and passing. When it stopped the air was a clear plasma of exaltation. To know that the binding forces of matter were yours to break, the wealth of nations yours to squander in such sublime force, this was a deep and secret sweetness known only to the few.</p>
<p>At the ranch now Thorpe was joking with some grad students from X Section. Others were there from J Section, and some stern faces he didn‚Äôt know, military or intelligence, and Steradian alert as a corrupt deputy. Highet arrived in blue jeans and tooled leather boots, carrying cases of soda, chanting in a false twang, ‚ÄìTwaace the sugar, twaace the caffeine‚Ä¶ followed by a Western senator cadaverous and grinning in white Stetson, and his young aide plump and groomed to a sheen, with the zealous black eyes of a <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/pullet" title="A young hen, especially one less than one year old.">pullet</a>.</p>
<p>‚ÄìLook at em, young, brilliant, confident, said the senator. ‚ÄìThat‚Äôs how I felt at their age. They own the world.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe world? retorted Highet. ‚ÄìThey own their genitals. The rest of them‚Äôs mine, raising his voice to introduce, ‚ÄìGentlemen, the right honorable Howard Bangerter of Utah‚Ä¶</p>
<p>The aide asked if physics had yet succeeded in finding in the traces of Creation the fingerprints of God, and Highet nodded, a slow smile spreading and his tonguetip darting as his hands rose to conjure, ‚ÄìNot God exactly‚Ä¶ as Quine walked onto the deck where three barbecue grills sizzled, and a keg of COORS LITE sat amid greasy paper plates bearing the ruins of meals, and the sun had long since chased the wandering moon, itself pursuing Venus, behind the mountain wall. Although the sky retained day‚Äôs blue a chill came down from the remote and snowless peaks.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThis young man, Highet‚Äôs voice carried out from within, won last year‚Äôs <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hertz%20Foundation" title="Wikipedia: Hertz Foundation">Heinrich Hertz Fellowship in Physics</a>, a prestigious award I happen to administer‚Ä¶ and Quine stepped down from the deck, crossing [pg58] dry grass to the creek‚Äôs rockstrewn willowed bank where it trickled through small pools and clumps of rotting leaves. Quine followed it upward, breath laboring. He stopped at a large boulder long ago tumbled from a higher place, and sat. Little residue of the day‚Äôs warmth remained in the shadowed stone. The western ridge above him was a great dark wave. In the east a glamour of rosetint clouds swept up from the horizon. The ranch was small below him. A cold wind came down the great wall of rock. Into this wilderness he might ascend and be lost.</p>
<p>But he returned. Thorpe‚Äôs voice came up as he slid open the glass doors, ‚Äìbackground, you know, trucks on the highway, that sort of thing. Other side of the spool you can see some small tremblors we had this afternoon. When the shot goes off we‚Äôll see more than a wiggle. But the real action‚Äôs on this screen here. At the site they‚Äôre recording everything for later analysis but data‚Äôs also piped to this workstation where this autocorrelation software gives us an immediate window on what‚Äôs happening. Red is intense energy, blue is, you know, less intense. We‚Äôre looking for sort of a red ringlike structure.</p>
<p>Quine watched the stylus quiver as about him others conversed. Without warning the stylus jerked. The screen of the workstation came to life, numbers flowing down its right edge. Colors coalesced on screen. The senator and his aide leaned in enrapt. A minute passed. Blue and green surrounded a corona of yellow and a jagged red core flecked with white.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWe have brightness, Thorpe said. ‚ÄìA hundred times the last test. More. Could be a thousand times.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThree orders of magnitude improvement, declared Highet. ‚ÄìAt this rate we‚Äôll have every enemy missile on Earth neutralized in a few years, and raising his tone with his glass, ‚ÄìTo Team Superbright! Leonardos of the age. You people are the best in the world.</p>
<p>Grunts and howls of triumph went off like rockets. The senator‚Äôs aide leaned smiling to whisper in the senator‚Äôs ear.</p>
<p>A second wave of guests arrived, a dozen men in suits adorned with MAMMOTH CONVENTION CENTER NAME COMPANY and a few women packaged as brightly as new software, and Quine moved off through the manic younger men hopped up by caffeine and sugar and the shot. [pg59]</p>
<p>‚ÄìNeed now‚Äôs another little war where we can demo this stuff. Feed some <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saddam%20Hussein" title="Wikipedia: Saddam Hussein">tinhorn tyrant</a> some antiquated missiles and provoke him to use them.</p>
<p>‚Äì<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PDP%20eleven" title="Wikipedia: PDP eleven">PDP eleven</a> downstairs running <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spacewar%20%28video%20game%29" title="Wikipedia: Spacewar (video game)">spacewar</a></p>
<p>‚Äìthought Malibu was bad but Acapulco‚Äôs about three inch waves</p>
