<p>‚ÄìIt was his demo.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, you saw to that. All right. We‚Äôll keep him on for a while. Then you‚Äôll write him a letter of recommendation. Down the road we‚Äôll issue a report on the false brightness. You‚Äôll be group leader on that.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou want me to‚Ä¶</p>
<p>Highet‚Äôs voice was tight with controlled fury. ‚ÄìI want you to take some responsibility. Show you‚Äôre serious about this. It‚Äôs about time you moved up or got out.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOkay.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou begin to interest me, Philip. I thought I knew what to expect from you.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAt least we caught this now.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOkay. I listened to your story. Now you listen to me. We haven‚Äôt caught a thing yet. What we need now is another test. [pg65]</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt want to sound naive, but you‚Äôre not going to mention this at the presentation?</p>
<p>‚ÄìToday? I think not. I think I will not at this moment give the enemies of reason grounds sufficient to bury our project, our knowledge, our aspirations. Highet lifted from his desk a small device etched with a craft undreamed of even a decade before, raising it before him like a talisman, weighing it in his hand. ‚ÄìI believe not.</p>
<p>Nolan came through the door bearing a red folder, acknowledged Quine with a minute change of expression, as the phone rang and Highet lifted it, ‚ÄìNo I can‚Äôt see anyone right now.</p>
