<p>‚ÄìBecause it seems, I mean, Highet is implicated in some of these investigations, it could appear improper that you were hired at a time when‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìI went over this with Lab counsel. You know, IRS agents sometimes go into private practice, you can hire them to represent you if [pg206] you‚Äôre audited. To me this is similar, an audit just goes easier if you have someone who knows the ropes, who can clarify issues for the auditors. I think Doctor Highet understood that, he certainly never said I was supposed to, well, cover anything up.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo no I‚Äôm not suggesting, just want to, to clarify‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell, my position. That I‚Äôm not condoning anything but full cooperation in any ongoing investigations.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOf course.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThen if we can, I want to look at this buffer zone business.</p>
<p>Rector opened a folder. ‚ÄìRight. Well, it seems that the toxics mitigation pilot program, Site Alpha, you know, the vineyard over the toxic plume, needs to be expanded.</p>
<p>‚ÄìExpanded? Why?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell, the plume is spreading offsite. The expansion brings it onsite again. Anyway, some people in E Section got wind of this, recommended it actually, and they bought land in the expansion zone.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThey thought they could make a profit selling the land back to the Lab? But that‚Äôs, what‚Äôs wrong with these people, don‚Äôt we pay them enough, that they have to pull this crap?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI think we can convince GAO to drop the investigation if the people involved make restitution.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIs that enough?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIf you want to reprimand them in some way, that‚Äôs your choice. But in the interests of the Lab‚Äôs ongoing situation, I‚Äôd say settle it and move on. Now we have the missing property and the unassigned overhead costs‚Ä¶ as Rector shifted the first folder to the bottom of his stack revealing the next, one inch thick.</p>
<p>‚ÄìLook, Jeremy, I‚Äôm sorry, but is this urgent? I meant twenty-four hour urgent?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell, no, I mean we have months to respond, but there‚Äôs a lot to get through and I thought</p>
<p>‚ÄìI know, I just, I‚Äôm just kind of jet lagged and I can‚Äôt really concentrate, so if you don‚Äôt mind‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìFine, and the calfskin case clicked together with the <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/chirm" title="(v.) To chirp or to make a mournful cry, as a bird does.">chirm</a> of the phone. [pg207]</p>
<p>‚ÄìHello?</p>
<p>‚ÄìEnjoy your weekend, Doctor Quine.</p>
<p>‚Äìjefe?</p>
<p>‚ÄìConor? Is that you?</p>
<p>‚Äìold me to cal</p>
<p>‚ÄìConor, I can‚Äôt, the phones are still. can you hear me?</p>
<p>‚Äìay?</p>
<p>‚ÄìLook I, if you can hear me, I, I, let‚Äôs not meet today, I‚Äôm going to leave early. Okay? Okay?</p>
<p>‚Äìk</p>
<p>He dropped the handset on the cradle, muttered and swept papers into his case, latched it, and strode into the outer office where ‚Äìa grass roots bottoms up effort, was suppressed as he entered.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOkay Dolores, I‚Äôm</p>
<p>‚ÄìDoctor R√©ti is on his way up.</p>
<p>‚ÄìChrist! Didn‚Äôt I tell you, as a knock sounded. His eyes darted around the room for an escape he knew wasn‚Äôt there from the inevitable he‚Äôd been putting off for months by cautious scheduling.</p>
<p>Morose, limping, R√©ti entered. He bore a gnarled staff taller than himself, and the expression of a man who‚Äôd spent too much time with fools.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDoctor R√©ti, it‚Äôs good to see you. Come, come in‚Ä¶ and Quine let the way into the inner office as R√©ti glanced dispassionately around the room.</p>
<p>‚ÄìSo. How is our young director getting on?</p>
<p>‚ÄìNot so young. Forty.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBefore I was forty, we had dropped atomic bombs on Hiroshima and Nagasaki. Just a few years later, I argued to build a laboratory, this one, to learn everything we could learn about nuclear weapons. So you are right. Forty is not so young. And now, almost half a century after the first bombs, we go on learning.</p>
<p>Quine said nothing. R√©ti stared past him at the drawn blinds, beyond which a jackhammer opened fire.</p>
<p>‚ÄìMay I sit? R√©ti gestured at a chair.</p>
<p>‚ÄìForgive me, of course, please.</p>
<p>R√©ti limped slowly to the chair and lowered himself into it. The [pg208] staff leaned against it like a limb of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yggdrasil" title="Wikipedia: Yggdrasil">Yggdrasil</a>. ‚ÄìBut that history is not important now. What is important now is to keep the Radiance program alive.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDoctor R√©ti, the administration and the Department of Energy have decided that our work on Radiance is over.</p>
<p>R√©ti pointed at him. ‚ÄìThis important knowledge, for which you and so many others fought so hard, must not be lost.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe knowledge gained was not, in my view, primarily scientific.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou do not yet understand, there are ways to keep programs alive, to reorganize their component parts. I will tell you how.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, but</p>
<p>The pointing finger raised. ‚ÄìOne moment. Many years ago, when I was for one semester a visiting professor at your university, and on your doctoral committee, I read your dissertation and I thought, here is a young man who understands physics. And when your paper on quanta was published with Sorokin, I knew that it was so. I lobbied strongly that you should have a Heinrich Hertz fellowship to come here. And you did excellent work. Now you are director, a rise of meteoric speed, and I wish to put at your disposal some of my experience.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou flatter me. My understanding of physics is not that deep. And the work I did on Radiance was deeply flawed. It led to a scandal.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe work is not flawed. The scandal is in the political necessities.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDoctor R√©ti, perhaps you forget. I worked on the Superbright x-ray laser for years. It didn‚Äôt work and we pretended it did. And we suffered the consequences.</p>
<p>‚ÄìMay I remind you that despite your own highly critical, one might almost say self-lacerating report, our entire team was exonerated by the General Accounting Office. The idea is still a good one. And that is why we must proceed with it on different terms. Now listen to me. I will tell you what we must do.</p>
<p>‚ÄìSir, with all due respect. I am director, and I am responsible to the Department of Energy. It is my decision.</p>
<p>R√©ti‚Äôs brows came together. He breathed heavily. ‚ÄìYou are not like Highet.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo, sir, I am not. I believe that‚Äôs why I was appointed.</p>
<p>R√©ti sat forward in his chair. His hands met between his knees. [pg209]</p>
<p>‚ÄìLook. My friend Leo Highet is an enthusiast for new ideas. Like me, he is an optimist. There is nothing wrong with that.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIn this case optimism became fraud.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI spoke well of you to the regents. I supported your candidacy. Despite that Leo Highet was my friend, and in my opinion ousted unfairly, I did so for the good of the Lab.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI appreciate that, sir.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI remember too that you visited me in the hospital. I should like to think of you as a friend.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou do me too much honor.</p>
<p>‚ÄìMy friend Leo Highet has his weaknesses, I do not deny it. But whatever else, he has passion. And he understand the political necessity of funding.</p>
<p>Leaning forward, R√©ti grasped the staff and stamped it upon the floor. ‚ÄìFunding comes from the threat. Now, this administration does not think that Russia is a threat. I say they are wrong. But even so, there is no shortage of threats. There is another great threat, and I do not mean the threat from north Africa to southern Europe. There is a threat of being hit by a comet, or asteroid. The last time it happened was in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tunguska%20event" title="Wikipedia: Tunguska event">Tunguska, Siberia</a>.<a href="#fn113" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref113"><sup>113</sup></a></p>
<p>‚ÄìIn nineteen hundred and eight, said Quine. He had heard this before. It was part of R√©ti‚Äôs road show. Following Tunguska he brought up <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicxulub%20crater" title="Wikipedia: Chicxulub crater">Chixculub</a> (Mayan, some said, for devil‚Äôs asshole) where during the Cretaceous Period, a meteor had hurled enough debris aloft to darken the earth, change its climate, and cause planetwide extinctions.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, in nineteen hundred and eight. I was then five months old. It was an aboveground explosion of ten million tons equivalent. Had it happened near a populated region, it would have been the biggest disaster, and we have excellent reason to believe that this disaster with appropriate notification can be averted. Here is a threat that is less probable than most other threats, but when it happens, it can become so big that, you know, it wiped out sixty-five million years ago the dinosaurs. That I think is a very interesting threat.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAccording to the secretary of energy, said Quine, ‚Äìthe Lab‚Äôs mission is now stockpile stewardship and management.</p>
<p>R√©ti fixed his eyes on Quine. ‚ÄìI understand you held a meeting. I [pg210] would have liked to attend.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm sorry, I thought you were out of town. It was urgent that we move forward.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI have no official duties. It is your prerogative to include me or not. But I will say that other directors have profited from my experience. I will say that I have always been notified of meetings.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôll see that you get complete minutes. It was a discussion of the stewardship program. We</p>
<p>Again the staff struck the floor. ‚ÄìStewardship. Do you know what <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/steward#Etymology">that word means</a>? It means you are warder of the sty. A keeper of pigs. Is that what you wish?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe stewardship program has interesting elements. For example, the Avalon laser.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, Avalon, do you think I don‚Äôt know? Avalon is ours by right. We have planned it for years. Since the very beginning of this Lab we have pursued inertial confinement fusion. I wrote the first papers on it. Now, this new administration wants a test ban treaty, which is impossible because Russia will cheat<a href="#fn114" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref114"><sup>114</sup></a>. And they think to buy our compliance with Avalon. I say we should have Avalon plus Radiance!</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs impossible. All missile defense work is now run by the Pentagon.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe Pentagon will not continue the x-ray laser.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPerhaps not.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOn which you worked so hard, gave so much.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou could look on Avalon as a way of continuing and vindicating Radiance‚Äôs x-ray laser work.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat will happen to J Section?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI can‚Äôt say at this time. There will be cuts.</p>
<p>‚ÄìListen to me. You must make a project to investigate the possible results of an asteroid impact. And the possibilities of protecting us from such an impact. And then you will find that much of Radiance, including Superbright and Slingshot, is also good for asteroid defense. Lasers, orbiting interceptors, nuclear weapons, all this can be repurchased. There is time to get all this into the budget request. There is support in Congress. We must have this!</p>
<p>‚ÄìFrankly, sir, I‚Äôm not sorry to see this missile defense work gone. [pg211] Many feel it‚Äôs a violation of the antiballistic missile treaty.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat treaty is no longer valid because the Soviet Union no longer exists. In any case, this work will never stop, because it has many powerful allies.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat do you mean?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou will see what I mean. And you will be sorry you let it slip away from you.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDoctor R√©ti, our budget may be down this year but</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt is not just the money! They cannot be allowed to tell us what to do. And in our work there must always be a nuclear component. Do you know why? Because they fear the nucleus. They respect it. And we are its masters. But now they would reduce us to simulations. This must not be. This would be our end.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWe have no choice.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you understand something, when Radiance started, I could go directly to the president and ask for funds. On one occasion I secured a hundred million dollars, just by asking. On another, sixty million. Just like that, and gnarled fingers rose and met but did not snap, ‚ÄìFrom black budgets. Now we have a new president. I cannot do that with this new president. So you must.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI can‚Äôt.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou must! Why do you resist this?</p>
<p>‚ÄìSir. Radiance cost us credibility, we lost good people over it, we lost the trust of our owners. We‚Äôll have nothing further to do with it, in name or in fact. That‚Äôs final.</p>
<p>R√©ti looked up sharply. Pale piercing eyes sunk in sagging flesh. He thrust himself forward, trying to stand. The head of his staff swipe the air. ‚ÄìYou must not! Must not! Permit such an end to our experiment. We must find the next enemy.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPlease! Quine stood at the moment R√©ti sank back into his chair, eyes cast to the floor, mouth open, lower lip pendulous. ‚ÄìDon‚Äôt excite yourself.</p>
<p>At last R√©ti looked up at Quine, eyelids trembling. ‚ÄìI am stupid, I am emotional, I am old. I had such hopes for you. Why do you not ask me? Months you have been here. You do not come to me, you do not ask me for advice, for counsel, for anything. This is not right. [pg212]</p>
<p>‚ÄìI apologize. I, I‚Äôve been busy, and you‚Äôre often not here.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOr perhaps you believe, as outsiders do, that I am some kind of monster? But you know better. In the old man‚Äôs eyes was an entreaty, in his voice a belligerence. ‚ÄìDo you know that I argued for a demonstration? To drop one atomic bomb over Tokyo Bay, or on an uninhabited island<a href="#fn115" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref115"><sup>115</sup></a>. There was not time enough, they said. It would be too difficult and expensive, they said, to build another bomb. That was the last time I attempted to influence policy. It is not a scientist‚Äôs place. But! I am not afraid to express my opinion as a private citizen! And for a moment R√©ti was silent, reflecting no doubt on the many times he had expressed, sometimes on Lab letterhead, his opinion as a private citizen, but the memories were perhaps not uniformly happy, for his eyes narrowed and when he went on his tone was confidential, as if he were unfolding some elaborate mystery.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNow I will tell you something. During the War, we all worked together, we all knew that the Bomb was important science and it was important to the world. We all felt that. When the War was over it changed. We were no longer together. There were two camps: make more, better bombs, or stop there. You would think that men so smart, so excellent in their field, could agree. It was obvious the Russians would build one. But no. And the strange thing was this. We were all excellent, all first rate, but even so, some were a bit above the rest, yes? And the very best, these were the men who did not want to go on making bombs. So when this Lab started, I became director, because I had no competition. I was the best of those who remained. The best of not the very best, do you see? I had won by a forfeit. My friends were no longer my friends. Now I talked with generals and senators, to whom physics was a magic trick. To whom I was a magus. That was my compensation. Nobel prizes for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niels%20Bohr" title="Wikipedia: Niels Bohr">Bohr</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugene%20Wigner" title="Wikipedia: Eugene Wigner">Wigner</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert%20Einstein" title="Wikipedia: Albert Einstein">Einstein</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernest%20Lawrence" title="Wikipedia: Ernest Lawrence">Lawrence</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enrico%20Fermi" title="Wikipedia: Enrico Fermi">Fermi</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold%20Urey" title="Wikipedia: Harold Urey">Urey</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isidor%20Isaac%20Rabi" title="Wikipedia: Isidor Isaac Rabi">Rabi</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hans%20Bethe" title="Wikipedia: Hans Bethe">Bethe</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Felix%20Bloch" title="Wikipedia: Felix Bloch">Bloch</a>. For me, the ear of generals and Presidents. Now you know something I never told even my good friend Leo Highet. Something I am maybe a little ashamed of. So that you will understand what this place is to me.</p>
<p>He extended the staff. ‚ÄìBut I will tell you further. I am right and they are wrong. The age of the heroic individual scientist is over. The bomb changed everything forever. From then on we work always in [pg213] teams, always funded by government. And government is not interested in <em>physis</em>, in <em>scientia</em>, they want <em>techne</em>. I saw this sooner and more clearly than any. So we give them what they want! And in return they permit us to go on with our work. And we are <em>not</em>, and Quine shrank from the fury and loathing he saw in R√©ti‚Äôs eyes, we are not <em>owned</em>.</p>
<p>Leaning on his staff, R√©ti got to his feet, shaking off Quine‚Äôs hand. When he had left, Quine sat trembling. He cleared his throat as if he would speak but said nothing. He rose and went to the bathroom where he ran water into a glass and reached for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valerian%20%28herb%29%23Medicinal%20use" title="Wikipedia: Valerian (herb)#Medicinal use">Valerian</a> 500 mg when the shrill of the phone turned him. He glanced at the mirror to find something vicious in the face there, something that hid itself as quickly as it had appeared.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes Dolores? All right, tell Conor I can‚Äôt see him this evening. I‚Äôm leaving now.</p>
<p>By the time he reached the road an anticipation of night stood in the east where the sun‚Äôs last rays raked tender green hills, an island of serenity beneath the ridge‚Äôs stubble of windmills, relics of a time before his time at the Lab when, however briefly, its mission has encompassed the passive generation of energy as well as its explosive deployment. The enemy? Where now is the enemy? His distracted gaze moved over the stopped traffic and the unfinished pylons of a freeway overpass separating on the one side a lighted plinth of signs <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circuit%20City" title="Wikipedia: Circuit City">Circuit City</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toys_%22R%22_Us">Toys ‚Äú–Ø‚Äù Us</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barnes%20%26%20Noble" title="Wikipedia: Barnes &amp; Noble">Barnes &amp; Noble</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Office%20Depot" title="Wikipedia: Office Depot">Office Depot</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bed%20Bath%20%26%20Beyond" title="Wikipedia: Bed Bath &amp; Beyond">Bed Bath &amp; Beyond</a>, from its counterpart on the other side proclaiming <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CompUSA" title="Wikipedia: CompUSA">CompUSA</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zany%20Brainy" title="Wikipedia: Zany Brainy">Zany Brainy</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Borders%20Group" title="Wikipedia: Borders Group">Borders</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Staples%20Inc." title="Wikipedia: Staples Inc.">Staples</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linens_%27n_Things">Linen ‚ÄôN Things</a>, and past those to the redtiled roofs of Estancia Estates which recalled an era so bygone it had never existed, a dream of California begun when Cortez‚Äôs men landed on the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baja%20peninsula" title="Wikipedia: Baja peninsula">Baja peninsula</a> which they mistook for the setting of the romance <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Las%20Sergas%20de%20Esplanadian" title="Wikipedia: Las Sergas de Esplanadian">Las Sergas de Esplanadian</a></em>, whose author <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garcia%20Ordonez%20de%20Montalvo" title="Wikipedia: Garcia Ordonez de Montalvo">Garcia Ordonez de Montalvo</a> averred that somewhere hereabouts was an enchanted isle of gold and pearls and griffins where Queen Califia‚Äôs black amazons dwelled and welcomed men once a year for purposes of procreation, and Cortez‚Äôs men in their hope (two girls for every boy!) or disappointment, or irony, gave the peninsula that empire‚Äôs name, whence the name traveled north to the Alta mainland and into a further dream [pg214] of gracious caballeros and se√±oritas kept ever fresh to ameliorate the zeal of the friars <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaspar%20de%20Portola" title="Wikipedia: Gaspar de Portola">Gaspar de Portola</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Junipero%20Serra" title="Wikipedia: Junipero Serra">Junipero Serra</a>, who in their exigent grace converted nearly as many natives as they enslaved, leaving the land vacant for the newest dream of Gracious Living in The Valley Starting in the $150,000 The Vineyard Starting in the $250,000 and The Glen Starting in the $350,000, where the only visible gold and pearl were the headlights and taillights of innumerable cars crawling past that green island of serenity dotted with the frames of new homes rising in the sun‚Äôs last rays like a tide of wrack up the hillsides. His eyes darted like animals in the cage of his anxious face, leapt from the darkening ground of nature to the lighted figures of man‚Äôs improvements upon it and back as if somewhere in this vast scribble and sprawl were signs to unlock the meaning of his slow unsteady progress, but the sign before him said EXIT NLY, and led only to more of the same.</p>
<p>As he entered the house he called out, ‚ÄìLynn? coming into the kitchen and glancing to the refrigerator where the calendar JANUARY was marked 6 PHILIP BACK and a red line crossed 24 through 31 LYNN IN GENEVA CTBT CONF and under 25 <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vandenberg%20Air%20Force%20Base" title="Wikipedia: Vandenberg Air Force Base">VANDENBURG</a> LAUNCH, and then to the sink, where apron strings were drawn tight across the trim back and flat shoulder blades up to closecropped black hair touched with russet. His shoes squeaked crossing the blue and white vinyl. She turned to him shaking water from her hands, smiling, wiping them on the apron. ‚ÄìWelcome home.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm glad to see you. God I‚Äôm tired. What a day.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI knew you wouldn‚Äôt call me back. So I just showed up.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI did call, I called you at home and at work.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut no message.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt like talking to machines.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAnd you don‚Äôt want to be overheard talking to me.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh, come on, I</p>
<p>‚ÄìEveryone knows about us anyway.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you think so?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou don‚Äôt sound very happy about it. She put her wiry arms around his neck.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm very happy. [pg215]</p>
<p>‚ÄìThank you, so am I.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs not a problem at work? Nobody‚Äôs mad?</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo, they think I‚Äôm going to convert you. And I will, too. Except Tony Luz is mad at me.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHe wants you for himself.</p>
<p>‚ÄìToo bad for him.</p>
<p>As he leaned in to kiss her a weight in him shifted but didn‚Äôt settle. Her lips smiled under his.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNow let me cook. Here. She handed him a glass of wine, golden and heavy.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThanks. What‚Äôs this about a lawsuit? I hear you‚Äôre suing us?</p>
<p>She bent to the oven, its door protesting as it opened. ‚ÄìWho, me? You must mean that peacenik outfit I work for.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThey‚Äôre the ones.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt seems you‚Äôve been careless with your EISes.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou don‚Äôt mean that oversight in the building plans, do you? We issued an errata.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNeed to know? She looked up, black eyes glinting.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOkay, sorry. I won‚Äôt ask. What are we having?</p>
<p>‚ÄìGrilled <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/portobello%20mushrooms" title="Wikipedia: portobello mushrooms">portobello mushrooms</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/risotto" title="Wikipedia: risotto">risotto</a> alla milanese, salad. Into the oven she slid a baking sheet bearing two mushroom caps big as hamburgers.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou spoil me.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI do indeed. Will you set the table?</p>
<p>On its surface was a vase of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/alstroemeria" title="Wikipedia: alstroemeria">alstroemeria</a> shedding striped petals into a bowl holding two <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bosc%20pears" title="Wikipedia: Bosc pears">Bosc pears</a> and two green apples, and onto a strew of newspaper clippings, <a href="http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-869220.html">US Forms Radiation Task Force</a>, Inexcusable Experiments, 33 Hospitals Were Involved In Cold War Radiation Experiments, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human%20radiation%20experiments%23Experiments%20performed%20in%20the%20United%20States" title="Wikipedia: Human radiation experiments#Experiments performed in the United States">Human Radiation Tests</a> Were Widespread, <a href="http://articles.mcall.com/1994-01-04/news/2969176_1_radiation-experiments-energy-department-white-house" title="White House Task Force To Probe Radiation Exposure">Prisoner Irradiation Probed</a>.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat‚Äôs all this?</p>
<p>She turned to him, a shallot in one hand, a paring knife in the other. ‚ÄìYou haven‚Äôt seen?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôve been busy.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip, this is a huge story. Doctors injected cancer patients with plutonium, they irradiated prisoners‚Äô testicles, they fed pregnant [pg216] women radioactive iron, all without their knowledge or consent. It really has the Auschwitz touch. And it‚Äôs not just them. It‚Äôs the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/downwinders" title="Wikipedia: downwinders">downwinders</a>, the</p>
<p>‚ÄìDown what?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe people who live downwind from the test site. All through the fifties when the bombs were going off, and they had no warning, no precautions, no compensation, the cancer rates are unbelievable, if you could hear these people talk, Philip. It‚Äôs heartbreaking. Can you hand me the salad bowl?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell, but, with testing stopped‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs not the point. This is the department‚Äôs history. You can‚Äôt bury history.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI thought you were preparing for the treaty talks.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI am. I‚Äôm following this because Janine, the reporter, has worked with us. You couldn‚Äôt have a better example of why people don‚Äôt trust DOE. They stonewalled Janine at every turn. Some of the documents were almost fifty years old and they still won‚Äôt come clean.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe new secretary wants to change things.</p>
<p>‚ÄìShe did the stonewalling.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut, she extended the ban on testing, she‚Äôs declassifying, and she did admit to these experiments, you saw her openness press conf</p>
<p>‚ÄìShe had no choice after the articles appeared. Anyway, she‚Äôs only admitted to eighteen victims, there are probably thousands. Now they‚Äôll form a task force and in a year or two they‚Äôll still be arguing over compensation.</p>
<p>Outside, beyond the black glass of the kitchen window, the yard went suddenly bright in the wind bending a tree tripping a motion sensor. He looked out at the tossing of the hedge some ten feet away, a wild motion constrained, chaos on the edge of complexity, until the floodlight snapped off. Then he returned to the clippings, Aguas Secas Desert Witness No More Bombs No More Tests.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDid you go to this? Were you at the test site?</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh, that. No, I stayed home this year. You show up, you listen to the usual homilies about peace, you get arrested and released. You spend three days validating each others‚Äô righteousness and at the end of it all nothing has changed. I always come home tired and grouchy. [pg217] Anyway I had too much to do getting ready for the CTBT. Are you changing the subject?</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo, I just‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip? Our agreement?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou don‚Äôt need to know anything about it. Really.</p>
<p>She scrutinized him. ‚ÄìAll right. I trust you. Sit. Eat. You look exhausted. Holding a baking sheet in an oven mitt she raised a mushroom on a spatula and placed it before him.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat a day. First the flight. Then a terrible, long meeting. Then R√©ti came to see me.</p>
<p>‚ÄìR√©ti?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôd been dreading it. He went on and on about this asteroid defense stuff, still trying to keep Radiance alive through it. He won‚Äôt give it up.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut surely after all the scandals‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìHe thinks we‚Äôve been exonerated. He thinks it‚Äôs a great success that we spent the Soviets into oblivion. Maybe he thinks we can outspend the asteroid belt too.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHe can‚Äôt keep that program alive, can he?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt know. Not as it was anyway.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôre under a lot of pressure.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou won‚Äôt believe what Highet did. Our new principal management analyst is one of the guys who wrote the GAO report on Radiance.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAre you really telling me this?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat do you mean? Of course. It‚Äôs so Highet, I thought you‚Äôd appreciate it.</p>
<p>‚ÄìSo are you going to fire this guy?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhy? He‚Äôs been vetted, and anyway he may be able to tell me something about Highet.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôve really got it in for Highet, don‚Äôt you?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou don‚Äôt?</p>
<p>‚ÄìCould we, I just want to not talk about it.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI always wondered where you got that report on Superbright. You had a copy even before I turned it in.<a href="#fn116" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref116"><sup>116</sup></a></p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip, you know I can‚Äôt tell you that. [pg218]</p>
<p>‚ÄìWas it Bran? Bran Nolan?<a href="#fn117" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref117"><sup>117</sup></a></p>
<p>‚ÄìPlease, I can‚Äôt tell you. Have some salad‚Ä¶ Arugula, watercress, sliced pears, hazelnuts, walnut oil, raspberry vinegar, rinsing it with the last of the Chardonnay, and then, ‚ÄìI have to look at some papers, here let me‚Ä¶ He rose to clear the table as, across the last of her wine, turning the glass by the stem, she watched him cross to the sink with dishes and return to the clippings bunched under the alstroemeria, pausing at Aguas Secas Desert Witness finally to say, ‚ÄìIs it necessary to call us <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor%20Strangelove" title="Wikipedia: Doctor Strangelove">Doctor Strangelove</a>s in your literature?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs not ours, Philip. That‚Äôs another group.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt is strange that I love you, don‚Äôt you think? In her eyes something worried, then fled. She stood up and pressed her mouth to his. Her breath to his. After a moment she broke it off. ‚ÄìBut I do love you, Philip.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, I‚Ä¶ I know. But‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you remember the first time we made love? I came over and told you to take my clothes off.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI remember.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI didn‚Äôt want to be carried away by the moment, I wanted to decide it. For so long I thought that getting involved with you was a terrible idea.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut you kept calling. I wondered if you wanted to use me.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThere was a little of that. But you, you wanted to be used.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, I did. By you.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou look, sometimes, you look so frustrated and disappointed, but under it there‚Äôs something else. Like you‚Äôre still looking for something. You haven‚Äôt given up. You didn‚Äôt just walk away from it all.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAre you sorry now that you have me?</p>
<p>She looked almost smiling up at him. ‚ÄìNo.</p>
<p>They passed through the living room where the dead eye of television reflected the entrance to a side room. ‚ÄìI don‚Äôt want to keep you from working, she said, a hand poised at her blouse, soon held in his, moving to caress and hold, as breaths quickened, hands moved and plucked more urgently where limbs stirred and came down in darkness on the bed as her heat enclosed him hungrily, her legs drawn back [pg219] for the swell of his entrance, her arms raised in a kind of supplication, the pale light from the street sketching her smoothness and firmness no longer an instigation but a reproach to his haggard flesh as he rolled onto his side and she came nestling after to embrace him and press the fronts of her warm thighs against the backs of his.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou poor. You‚Äôre so tired. Just sleep.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm sorry. I‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt doesn‚Äôt matter. Just sleep.</p>
<p>As his eyes closed his face slackened to a repose almost like its childhood, some mocking semblance of an innocence he‚Äôd inadvertently held through the passing of time and buffeting of experience that had turned it into this lined and sunken parody.</p>
<p>Somewhere within this stricken countenance he wandered in hallways that turned one into another, past WET PAINT and curious figures turning to watch, the corridor narrowing to a closed door where the knob turned and turned unavailing and a waspish voice said, ‚Äìa terrible administrator, lost control of the meeting, thinks you can bury the past, and ‚ÄìPhilip!</p>
<p>‚ÄìHuh, what!</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou were having a bad dream. It‚Äôs all right.</p>
<p>He shivered as she held him. In the streetlight the line of her lip was archaic, without sympathy or flaw, more unforgiving than her youth. He thought of Nan and his heart quailed.</p>
</section>
<section id="two-1" class="level3">
<h3>Two</h3>
<p>[pg220] Rainless January gave way to winter storms that blew in one after another with no break, stacked like <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erinyes" title="those who beneath the earth punish whosoever has sworn a false oath">waiting furies</a> over the Pacific, driven to landfall by a jetstream which, satellite photos showed, thrashed like an unmanaged firehose yet somehow kept its business end trained on the Bay Area, so that as the new year wore on what had been the direst winter on record threatened to become the wettest, said the newspaper Quine shook free of its yellow sheath, water falling on the seat beside him, and turned braking for orange cones around a truck EBMUD at a broken hydrant laving the flooded street as booted workmen in orange slickers waved him to DETOUR the wrong way down Codornices, onto a curving road at the edge of town heading into a rain that obscured any landmarks. He fidgeted the radio on to ‚Äìwidely expanded alcohol and drug testi, stilling it for the slap of wipers barely clearing the sheets of water that rippled over vagueness until the Lab gates loomed and he parked under RESERVED DIRECTOR. He dashed through the outer door and in the hallway still rushing overtook two men who didn‚Äôt glance up from, ‚ÄìThou shalt not piss on a colleague‚Äôs funding‚Ä¶ as he turned a corner into ‚ÄìBran!</p>
<p>‚ÄìMorning Philip. Slow down you‚Äôll live longer.</p>
<p>‚ÄìListen I need to talk to y</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm on my way to a diversification seminar, can it wait?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell sure but</p>
<p>‚ÄìToo bad, I‚Äôd like to miss this thing. [pg221]</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell come by my office later, will you‚Ä¶? as he jabbed an unyielding 5 for the blessed but temporary solitude of brushed stainless steel, pulling Ohlone Val from its plastic sheath and unfolding it to Lab Hiring Criticized By Antinuke Group, for a stunned moment ‚ÄìDamn her! and a trail of water tracking him to his office where the radio was ‚Äìworried he was doing to do danger to himself, until he closed the inner door and stopped short of his desk where ‚ÄìConor? sat.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThink I found your problem. Disk is all messed up, you should have a lot more free space than it says here. Looks like a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disk%20partitioning" title="Wikipedia: Disk partitioning">partition</a> was removed but not erased, I‚Äôm trying to recover it‚Ä¶ come on now, give me a break here, as Quine came around to peer at the screen.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat‚Äôs this, thirty eight directories thirteen thousand files three point one gigab</p>
<p>‚ÄìLooks like he never threw anything away.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHighet?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôd‚Äôve thought he‚Äôd encrypt everything, look at these directories, docs, contacts, 4thgen, xxx, what‚Äôs xxx? Thousands of files here, as the screen filled with a face framed in carrot red hair and lips pouted to kiss, ‚ÄìWhat, Conor, what is this?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell it‚Äôs not a Polish sausage is it. Looks like one of those GIF files they found on the sparta node back when. Want me to delete them?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThought we did that, yes Dolores what‚Ä¶? turning to follow her stare back to the screen beyond them. ‚ÄìSome old files of Highet‚Äôs, we were just</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôre due in the conference room at ten.</p>
<p>‚ÄìRight, just one, as the door swung shut. ‚ÄìWhy that woman doesn‚Äôt knock‚Ä¶ Conor, can we get back to this later?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYeah sure, just let me, uh huh, here we go, I thought so, as down the screen spilled<a href="#fn118" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref118"><sup>118</sup></a></p>
