<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs Highet‚Äôs public key. You know, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pretty%20Good%20Privacy" title="Wikipedia: Pretty Good Privacy">Pretty Good Privacy</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phil%20Zimmerman" title="Wikipedia: Phil Zimmerman">Phil Zimmerman</a>‚Äôs encryption software? The feds call strong encryption a munition, they‚Äôre prosecuting Zimmerman for exporting munitions.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI thought, I mean, isn‚Äôt <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data%20Encryption%20Standard" title="Wikipedia: Data Encryption Standard">DES</a> the federal encryption standard?<a href="#fn119" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref119"><sup>119</sup></a></p>
<p>‚ÄìGuess he didn‚Äôt trust it enough to use on his personal files.</p>
<p>‚ÄìCan this PGP be cracked?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIn theory, anything can be cracked. In reality, this is a two thousand forty-eight bit key. DES, that‚Äôs only fifty-six bits. Give me a week on our fastest computer and maybe I could crack DES for you, but this, forget about it. Unless you can guess his password.</p>
