<p>‚ÄìSee, I don‚Äôt think he knows himself. A wireless satellite net looks [pg235] good to shareholders. But reasons are a dime a dozen, and everybody fools themself. Now Gate, he‚Äôs a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mormon" title="Wikipedia: Mormon">Mormon</a>. A Latter Day Saint. Who believes that <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mormon%20cosmology" title="Wikipedia: Mormon cosmology">God</a> was once a man living on another planet. And that men will become gods populating other worlds.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat does that have to do wi</p>
<p>‚ÄìSee, that‚Äôs the heart of it. The unreason behind his reasons. You want to know why a man does what he does, look to his unreason, to whatever he follows despite all evidence and discouragement. Gate believes in external progression. He wants to go into space because he aspires to the highest places. Look at Highet, you wouldn‚Äôt take him for a believer, but for all his worldly cynicism, he has no use for the mammon of unrighteousness. He‚Äôs a child of light. It vexes him that R√©ti, a Hungarian Jew and a man of science, sups with fundamentalists. His faith in reason is his unreason. Leo thinks religion is ignorance, the enemy of science. But he‚Äôs wrong. Sir Isaac Newton, <a href="http://galileo.rice.edu/Catalog/NewFiles/bacon.html">Francis Bacon</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kepler" title="Wikipedia: Kepler">Kepler</a>, Priestley, Boyle, Faraday, James Clerk Maxwell, these were devout and prayerful men who looked for the apocalyptic coming of Christ. There‚Äôs no contradiction. They all wanted to bend creation to man‚Äôs will. To find if the fury in their hearts was God‚Äôs or some other‚Äôs. Why, you have quite a few of the saved right here within your walls<a href="#fn126" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref126"><sup>126</sup></a>. And what better place for them? Are they not stewards?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôre a religious man?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI am not. That claptrap makes me puke. And you?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt have an opinion.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAgnostic? Looking for proof? Do you think what Bacon thought, that God left his fingerprints on the creation? Then hid them from us like some <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/cypherpunk" title="Wikipedia: cypherpunk">cypherpunk</a>? Like Leonardo‚Äôs mirror writing?</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo opinion.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm not saying He didn‚Äôt. But if He did hide the sign of His being, would it not be in the atom? The nuclear reaction is the source of light, of energy, of the universe itself. Isn‚Äôt that why we study it? But Leo never understood that light can‚Äôt conquer darkness. It only pushes it back for a time. Who wants to live in that light? That‚Äôs why we build houses. That‚Äôs why we build churches. That‚Äôs why we build labs.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOkay look, I‚Äôm</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut what do you believe? What‚Äôs your purpose here? [pg236]</p>
<p>‚ÄìHere? I‚Äôm here to serve the national interest.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe national interest! Why, that‚Äôs unassailable. Can you tell me what it is?</p>
<p>‚ÄìAccording to DOE it‚Äôs stockpile stewardship and nonproliferation.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs quite a job of work. You got the former Soviet republics bein looted, you got Kazakh nuclear scientists gone unpaid for two years, you got four hundred reactors in the world that by the time they shut down they‚Äôll have produced a million kilos of plutonium. Somebody kicked over the anthill and you‚Äôre gonna keep track of every last ant? You can mess with your sensors and analysis techniques and inventories, but that‚Äôs just playin keep away. Few more years we‚Äôll all be nostalgic for two player mutual assured destruction, know what I mean? So there‚Äôs all the more need now for missile defense, it‚Äôs a perennial, you‚Äôd do well to remember that. Ever since the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V-2%20rocket" title="Wikipedia: V-2 rocket">V2s</a> hit London. Time after time the military studies it and gives it up. But you <em>can</em> hit a bullet with a bullet. To hit a hundred bullets, among a thousand decoys, not to miss a one, that‚Äôs difficult and expensive. But it is possible. The man in the street don‚Äôt care what it costs, he just wants to feel safe. There‚Äôs national interest for you. Anyway we have assets in space. Put assets in space you have to protect them now don‚Äôt you.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt think anyone‚Äôs really asked the man in the street what he wants.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou truly want democracy on a thing like this? When everybody‚Äôs so harassed by daily life they can‚Äôt think straight even if they‚Äôd ever learned how? Mom and dad both working fifty hour weeks to pay down the credit cards while the kids play <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super%20Nintendo%20Entertainment%20System" title="Wikipedia: Super Nintendo Entertainment System">Nintendo</a> it‚Äôs no wonder you got all those suburban muscle trucks on the road, corner a wounded animal he‚Äôll make a face looks just like that. Democracy? It‚Äôs a miracle they don‚Äôt kill each other. Meantime they just want to feel safe, whatever it costs in the long run, fuck the long run, they‚Äôre living on usury so why not make them feel safe and help yourself to the float? The beauty part is, you don‚Äôt have to deliver the safety, so long as they have someone to blame but themselves.</p>
<p>‚ÄìSo money, that‚Äôs your reason? [pg237]</p>
<p>‚ÄìMoney interests me as a force. You know, this <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis%20Fukuyama" title="Wikipedia: Francis Fukuyama">Fukuyama</a> fellow with his talk about <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The%20End%20of%20History%20and%20the%20Last%20Man" title="Wikipedia: The End of History and the Last Man">the end of history</a><a href="#fn127" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref127"><sup>127</sup></a>, the triumph of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/liberal%20capitalism" title="Wikipedia: liberal capitalism">liberal capitalism</a>, I got news for him, he ain‚Äôt even seen capitalism yet. Till now we‚Äôve had the playschool version. Real capitalism is just warmin up. Just you wait. Money? Trillions gone be flyin in the air up for grabs. But I‚Äôm only interested as a student of the world. If money was my thing I‚Äôd buy real estate. Course I want a decent return on my investment, like everybody else.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI have to get on with my day.</p>
<p>‚ÄìCourse you do. You‚Äôre a busy man. Root grimaced as he pushed his bulk up from the chair. ‚ÄìOne more thing. Devon Null left some papers here.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat do you know about Null?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou shared office space he told me. Though you might know what become of them papers.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you know, I never once saw Devon Null.</p>
