<p>‚ÄìAnd you want me? For a moment Szabo‚Äôs hunger and mistrust and resentment stood in a visible equilibrium, and a kind of terror rose in Quine at his own daring.<a href="#fn129" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref129"><sup>129</sup></a></p>
<p>‚ÄìWe‚Äôve had our differences, Frank, but you‚Äôre a capable scientist and manager, as he straightened papers on the desk and then looked up suddenly as if to ambush the suspicion and hope at war in Szabo‚Äôs face.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôd want to talk to Bill about it, he said.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt‚Äôs not up to Bill. Quine glanced at his watch and picked up the [pg243] phone. ‚ÄìI‚Äôll talk to you tomorrow, Frank.</p>
<p>After the door closed he put down the phone and stood gazing out the window, past the torn and lakeleted pit, past the dry fountains, to where the sun broke for a moment through clouds, its brilliance surprising the white ramparts of Building 101 and illuminating the people before it as though <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salomon%27s%20House" title="Wikipedia: Salomon's House">Solomon‚Äôs House</a> had risen from the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New%20Atlantis" title="Wikipedia: New Atlantis">New Atlantis</a> and with it these elite and stainless angels of progress, lambent in their moment of <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/instauration" title="restoration after decay or dilapidation; renewal; repair">instauration</a>, only to be swallowed again in the sullen shadow of a cloud, like a blessing glimpsed then withdrawn, a grace fickle as the air that sustained it and sent the vision‚Äôs acolytes now scurrying for shelter ahead of its chill, doors slammed and heater punched to HI as he waited through two changes of the light for cars in the turn lane inching forward finally to permit him into the parking lot, where he crept over yellow and black speed bumps past Zany Brainy and REG L C NEM S M X and Linda Evans and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New%20Economy" title="Wikipedia: New Economy">New Economy</a> Dry Cleaners and œà Psychotherapy Associates, until at Starbucks a heavy truck VANITY driven by a blonde with a phone to one ear backed smartly out of a space, HONOR ROLE PARENT ALISAL ELEMENTARY looming closer and closer between the tires‚Äô inch-thick tread until be abruptly geared into reverse and lurched back three feet to the sound of a horn behind him and his engine‚Äôs sudden stall. The horn blared twice more as he turned the ignition key, and the offended driver shot around him turning sharply into the vacated space. When his engine caught he eased the car another hundred feet to another space and walked back to Starbucks Grand Opening where a line of people stretched out the door.</p>
<p>Up in the gray sky fleeted a ghost of blue. At the door of the caf√© he paused, watching her just inside in a kind of half light before the dimness, the back of her neck aglow where a veil of fine auburn hair traced with gray fell across its paleness. As if sensing his gaze there her hand came up to brush the hair aside, exposing the volutions of her ear before it fell back and she stepped forward into the dimness. When she took her seat he came toward her. There was strain in her face when she looked up.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHere, sliding across the table a thin manila folder bordered in red and white strips. ‚ÄìDo you have a need to know this? Or are you [pg244] just curious?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI just want to, as he opened the folder and scanned the single page within, Memorandum of Understanding Between Laboratory and Contractor, security clearance, right and title to intellectual property to be negotiated case by case, glancing up to find her eyes steady on him.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat are you looking for, Philip?</p>
<p>His eyes moved down the single page and back up it in a vain search for he wasn‚Äôt sure ‚Äì What? Oh. The university has all employees sign an agreement, a patent agreement, everyone signs it, you have to, but see if Devon Null was only a contractor he could have had a waiver he could just walk out the door with whatever work he‚Äôs</p>
<p>‚ÄìI wasn‚Äôt asking about Null.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut you see if he never worked here‚Ä¶</p>
<p>She sighed and closed her purse. ‚ÄìPhilip, I have things to do.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo wait, I‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìThis file isn‚Äôt what you want to talk about. Because you could have called anyone for it, had it sent to your office.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut yes, it is, I mean</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou won‚Äôt give me an inch, will you? Philip, it‚Äôs been over a <em>year</em>. I thought you would at least call me. Or even come back, once, to say goodbye. But you didn‚Äôt. And I gave up waiting. Why are we here now? Because you want employee records?</p>
<p>Her voice had opened further perhaps than she‚Äôd intended, and her mouth showed its distress at this betrayal of her defenses by the very tremor of those words trying not to say all of what she meant.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, but it was, it was also a reason to see you, Nan‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìHow little you must think of me, Philip.</p>
<p>‚ÄìTo say I‚Äôm sorry.</p>
<p>Suddenly his eyes filled. Hers in turn dropped their guard. After a moment she reached for his hand. They sat in silence for a moment as she regarded him, waiting perhaps for the more that, she seemed now to remember, never came. She withdrew her hand and looked down at it, as if surprised and not particularly pleased at its boniness, the lines in the knuckles, the pale skin creased near a ring.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAnd now you‚Äôre acting director. I wouldn‚Äôt have guessed it. I [pg245] thought you were ready to have a breakdown or quit. And it turns out that you were maneuvering.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat‚Äôs not what happened.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou stepped over so many people. What a change in you.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut I, it wasn‚Äôt, have I really changed so much?</p>
<p>Again she regarded him with level curiosity.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNo, Philip, you haven‚Äôt really changed. You never gave anyone an inch. I just never thought‚Ä¶ but she shook off whatever it was she hadn‚Äôt wanted to think.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut no, I, that was Highet who</p>
<p>‚ÄìI worked for Leo Highet once. He was a jerk, but you knew where you stood with him. With you I always had to guess. When I guessed wrong, you took it out on me.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNan‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou were such a, an artichoke, Philip. I could never find your heart.</p>
<p>He glanced away, as if unwilling to encounter in those gray eyes what he‚Äôd failed to see in himself. ‚ÄìAre you well? How are things?</p>
<p>She continued to regard him with that watchful uncertainty. ‚ÄìI‚Äôm fine. I‚Äôm short on sleep. There‚Äôs new construction behind my house, it‚Äôs very annoying, it used to be open space, you remember. Trucks come in at six a m dumping dirt.<a href="#fn130" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref130"><sup>130</sup></a> You know what a poor sleeper I am. Philip, why are we here?</p>
<p>He looked in agony around the caf√©. ‚ÄìI never knew what you wanted of me. What you expected.</p>
<p>Her face softened. ‚ÄìOh, Philip, I never‚Ä¶ I just wanted you to be, to be what you sometimes can be, just now for such a brief moment, just to be happy in your skin. To be content with, with things.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI was, I was content with us. As best I could be. I was content and not content, don‚Äôt you see‚Ä¶ As he spoke he leaned slowly forward and opened his hands. But she seemed resolved now to resist contact. Without moving she drew herself back.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip, I‚Äôm getting married.</p>
<p>A stone fell in him. ‚ÄìYou‚Äôre, but I, but who‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou remember Ben. You used him as an excuse to break up with me. [pg246]</p>
<p>‚ÄìNan‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe wedding is in July. I‚Äôll send you an invitation.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNan, I‚Ä¶ He blinked in fury, then pressed fingers to his eyes.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip. Her hand touched his forearm and he flinched from it.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm sorry, Nan. I have no right. I treated you very badly.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, you did. But I know you were in pain. Over your work, and more. I could have tried harder. To allow for that.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWere you, sorry, when I left?</p>
<p>She seemed to consider. ‚ÄìNo, not at first. At first I was relieved. Not to have to deal with it anymore. Whatever was eating you up. Then I was lonely, very lonely. For months. I hated you then. Hated that you didn‚Äôt call, that you could just walk away like that.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI was hurting, too.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, I suppose you were. I told myself that you were. That you‚Äôd get through it and then you‚Äôd call me.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI still hurt. The truth of it went through his body like a shock.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut you‚Äôre seeing someone.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThat young anti-nuclear activist.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHow did you</p>
<p>She drew back. ‚ÄìOh, Philip, everyone in the Lab knows. Anyway, you were looking for someone else even when we were together.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut I, no, I</p>
<p>‚ÄìDid you think I couldn‚Äôt tell? That was what hurt most. She‚Äôs much younger, isn‚Äôt she.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNot so much.</p>
<p>Her hand clasped her cup. She said with bitterness, ‚ÄìDoes she make you feel younger, is that it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìNan, please‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìI swore to myself that if you ever talked to me again I wouldn‚Äôt‚Ä¶ She looked away and sat stiffly in a kind of abstracted misery until she could face him again. ‚ÄìDid you ever really love me?</p>
<p>‚ÄìNan‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìBecause I did love you. I felt, all that time, despite everything, all our differences, the distance you wanted to keep, that we held each other in trust. [pg247]</p>
<p>‚ÄìI, and he swallowed with difficulty, his breath was short, his eyes burned. ‚ÄìI wanted to give you my heart.</p>
<p>She sat looking at his face. ‚ÄìYou had a funny way of showing it. No, I‚Äôm sorry. I‚Äôm sure you did want that. She rose and bent toward him, pressed her soft lips to the hinge of his jaw.</p>
<p>‚ÄìGoodbye, Philip.</p>
<p>The sun dimmed, bled whitely into opal sky. Everything seemed to lose itself in the middle of time. He‚Äôd sat like this, here in this lot, so long ago, when Kate had told him, not unkindly, oh Philip, it‚Äôs too late for us. The moment‚Äôs passed. The same sun dimmed in cloud, the same hollowness. He wanted the pain of it again. Anything but this middle.</p>
<p>Seeking an exit his car heaved over one yellowstriped <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/loma#Spanish">loma</a> after another, past Linens ‚ÄôN Things, Blenzers, Leather For Le<span class="math">$$$</span>, Hacienda House, Mattress Discounters, Dent Removers, heading toward the main road but reaching a curb that cut him off from it, turning parallel to the curb past the back of Circuit City where barriers turned him back from further construction to a blank wall and dumpsters where he turned sharply to brake at DO NOT ENTER SEVERE TIRE DAMAGE forcing him into a smaller lot where Ah-d√≥r-no Hair Salon, En-Dev‚ÄôR Computers, Try Us <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bail%20Bonds" title="Wikipedia: Bail Bonds">Bail Bonds</a> ushered him out upon First American Title and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coldwell%20Banker" title="Wikipedia: Coldwell Banker">Coldwell Banker</a> to the promise of an EXIT and NO LEFT TURN. As he stared in that foreclosed direction waiting for a break in the traffic, a woe beyond pain rose in him, at what he‚Äôd never valued enough to feel the loss of, it came to him now, the pent and denied longings of his baffled heart rising briefly to an apprehension of the true scale of his grief, before submerging again into the remorselessness of the everyday and the freeway to Codornic s XIT NLY, and into his driveway where he stilled the car and sat in gathering darkness listening for he didn‚Äôt know what. On some road out of sight was some obstruction, a metal plate or a loose manhole cover, and from it came a hollow thump that echoed briefly as vehicles passed over and were gone, echoed through him like a tocsin of loss. As he opened the car door, wind harried the papers on the seat beneath his hand which clamped them and tucked them firmly under one arm before he dashed through a bluster of rain flung from the sky against [pg248] the door slammed hard on fully gathered night, as he wandered from one room to the next, into the kitchen where it seemed a voice muttered, masked by the refrigerator‚Äôs motor, rising from time to time almost high enough to make itself understood, until the motor shut off, and in its shadow came the murmurous drip of water in the sink, buried then by the whine of the microwave heating dinner, carried with a glass of golden wine to the sofa where at last he settled papers before him, the mutterings of the house submerged in the unattended flicker of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The%20X-Files" title="Wikipedia: The X-Files">The Truth Is Out There</a>.</p>
<p>Saturday morning came complacently into the house, lingering in the nearly bare rooms, touching blond wood and pale fabric, chrome and glass, browsing at the laminate bookshelf where <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The%20One%20Minute%20Manager" title="Wikipedia: The One Minute Manager">The One Minute Manager</a> leaned in to touch <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/7%20Habits%20of%20Highly%20Effective%20People" title="Wikipedia: 7 Habits of Highly Effective People">7 Habits of Highly Effective People</a> and <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Principle-Centered-Leadership-Stephen-R-Covey/dp/145589348X?tag=gwernnet-20">Principle-Centered Leadership</a> stood up to <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Managing-Speed-Change-Daryl-Conner/dp/0679406840?tag=gwernnet-20">Managing At the Speed of Change</a> and <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Stewardship-Choosing-Service-Self-Interest-Expanded/dp/1620648318?tag=gwernnet-20">Stewardship: Choosing Service Over Self Interest</a> had given over its struggle to hold back <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Thriving-Chaos-Handbook-Management-Revolution/dp/0060971843?tag=gwernnet-20">Thriving On Chaos</a> which sat heavily upon <a href="http://tonysmithconsulting.com/personal-growth-philosophy/">Parsifal‚Äôs Briefcase</a> upheld by cassette tapes Remember To Breathe, passing all by to follow the path sick sorrow took, finding Quine out in the kitchen for coffee and oranges by a sunny chair, only to lose him again in the one room that showed, in its dim disorder, anything like life, what Lynn called his mess room, a desk with papers strewn like leaves across its surface, a computer monitor topped by a seamsplit cardboard carton sagging like a heavy bough and beside the desk a banker‚Äôs box DESTROY AFTER and D NULL upended now for a flood of papers folders xeroxes and a curious small white stone figure crudely carved, some kind of dog perhaps, put aside while he sorted printouts, some of them ten years old or more, accordion fold <a hr