<p>‚ÄìLynn‚Ä¶ He rose, but she didn‚Äôt move, stood with her arms pulled close around her and stared as if at some future she could pull into being or banish with her next words. But abruptly she shook her head.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôm sorry Philip, I know I come on too strong, it scares people, I don‚Äôt want to scare you.</p>
<p>He embraced her warmth. Her tongue filled the emptiness of his mouth. What we want from another is so simple. Almost anyone will do. For a time at least the heart bonds as if it‚Äôs found its other, cloven half. Is this illusion? Something neither commanded nor freely given? If the heart can be so needful and so indiscriminate, how trust it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìPlease come upstairs.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes okay‚Ä¶ I just want to brush my teeth‚Ä¶ Water entered a whirlpool, rising and falling around the rim of the drain.</p>
