<p>‚ÄìDoes Highet know all this?</p>
<p>‚ÄìHighet invited him.</p>
<p>Quine headed for the door, passing as he did Andrew Steradian, holding a small microphone before a J Section technician, saying, ‚Äìyou‚Äôre so goldang busy every day you just put off thinking about it, though in Quine‚Äôs view pressure was a tool well used to put off thinking.</p>
<hr />
<p>Black cottonwoods around the pool throve despite the drought. Catkins littered the water. A jet moved in the sky, stitching a contrail across the thin lace of cloud drifting eastward through which a hot sun struggled to assert itself. Quine sat on a towel on the grassy verge and watched a portly bearded swimsuited man enter through the gate, barrel chest glossed with sunbleached hair, and behind him a woman in a white halter top and shorts, the heads of three men turning to follow. The pool was crowded this Friday afternoon; unlike Quine, most worked a five-day week, most would depart hence into a forgetfulness. In the shallows of the pool two young girls splashed. One opened her mouth to show her companion a bright penny on her outstretched tongue. A young mother in a black maillot gripped a ladder to raise herself half from the pool and wave at her infant in a nearby stroller, glisten and shadow in the cords of her back, and Quine suffered a pang for a life now beyond his knowing: to be wed, with child, so young. On thermals a blackwinged bird, <em>Cathartes aura</em>, rocked and banked. Jet‚Äôs thunder fell like muffled blows. The warmth and the sound of water churned by swimmers and the spray tossed up by their passing lulled Quine into a lethargy from which he woke with a start to consult his watch. On the pool‚Äôs floor danced cusps of light.</p>
<hr />
<p>When he parked at the town‚Äôs central mall the high cloud had passed and the sky was pale blue overhead and scum brown near its horizons. Quine walked sweating between pastel columns under a pediment that alluded to no place or time between smoked glass doors into an atrium so chill and disjunct it might have been another planet. Outside methane and ammonia storms might blow. Shops, granite benches, low fountains, and climbing plants ringed a pool in which stood a steel sculpture of crippled symmetry, as if a Platonic solid had ruptured.</p>
<p>The cafe‚Äôs high walls rose past exposed beams and ducts to the nacre of frosted skylights. Lynn sat at a glass table in a wireframe chair, face downcast [pg237] at papers before her. In the moment before she looked up, Kate‚Äôs face glowed before him. In this cafe they‚Äôd first talked. What do you do, Philip?</p>
<p>‚ÄìHoy es el d√≠a de los muertos, Lynn said in greeting, banishing Kate‚Äôs image. Angularities all her own moved in her flesh; a small gap showed between her teeth as she smiled.</p>
