<p>Outside Highet‚Äôs office Quine, arm raised to knock, from within heard Highet‚Äôs insistent rasp, ‚Äìlike Kammerer, you know, it‚Äôs not who makes the mistake it‚Äôs who takes the blame, and at Thorpe‚Äôs voice barely audible, ‚Äìsorry for the poor son of a bitch stuck in his position at his age, barely shows his face, and Highet, ‚Äìnever passed a design review, Quine‚Äôs ears flared with heat, the door before him turning flat and insubstantial as he lowered his hand and proceeded down the hall unseeing, guided by a familiarity more the prisoner‚Äôs than the adept‚Äôs around a corner to a water fountain, studying a bulletin board and its overlapping notices O Section, programmer needed to model underground plumes, K Section, LASS expert needed, Z Section, multimedia guru, B Section, materials engineer, while two young men passed, one saying, ‚ÄìI have no special loyalty to OOP, and on to a further junction where a convex mirror above him presented an anamorphic view around the corner. There Nan emerged from a cross corridor with a wiry black-haired man in a blue knit shirt, his biceps [pg242] and forearms hard and tanned. The two spoke briefly. The man put a hand on Nan‚Äôs neck and bent forward to kiss her mouth. Quine turned back the way he had come, slowing only when he found he had nearly circled the building. He backtracked to Highet‚Äôs door and entered without knocking. Highet was alone.</p>
<p>‚ÄìGet Thorpe out of my office.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWhat‚Äôs your problem now, Philip?</p>
