<p>‚ÄìDid he now. Well, we‚Äôre a team. Good results show good management.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôd like Jef to give the presentation.</p>
<p>Highet‚Äôs eyes fixed in calculation on Quine as the phone rang and Quine waited for the dismissive wave with which Highet ended audiences, but instead he spoke a moment, then covered the mouthpiece and said, ‚Äìwant to make some money Philip, Devon Null‚Äôs taking on investors, and uncovering the mouthpiece, ‚Äìyes, application‚Äôs outside the envelope no problem there, keep me briefed, and in another moment hung up, leaning back and clasping his hands over his thinning crown, gazing at the ceiling.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell that‚Äôs fine, that‚Äôs very fine. Wonder if we could work up a little something. I could invite some key people to the ranch for the shot, some unnamed sources, goose the process a little, can we get Thorpe in on this? [pg255]</p>
<p>‚ÄìHe‚Äôs probably in my office.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou may work out yet Philip, Highet grudged as one thick finger stabbed the phone. ‚ÄìJef? Leo. Get your ass over here, rising to pace past framed and signed photos of three presidents, another of R√©ti and himself with the current president, artist‚Äôs renderings of the Superbright and of a fusion-driven spaceship, cartoon of a mushroom cloud WHEN YOU CARE ENOUGH TO SEND THE VERY BEST, certificates from professional societies, a length of cable, a circuit board. He stopped at the windows, gaze caught by something, and parted the vertical slats of the blind with his fingers, speaking softly, almost to himself.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you know the darkness that‚Äôs out there? Do you realize how tenuous this all is? Twenty thousand years of civilization, and only in the last five hundred has rationality begun to displace superstition. I tell you that I would sup with the devil, I would court armageddon, not to lose that. When I think of those fucking tree huggers out there‚Ä¶ and turning back to Quine, voice low and insistent, ‚ÄìThink the ills are in a system, think it‚Äôs that simple, R√©ti with his anticommunism, your new girlfriend and her peacenik buddies, wonder why‚Äôs she drawn to you?</p>
<p>Quine said nothing.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDarkness and malady is in the human heart, Philip, you can‚Äôt eradicate it, don‚Äôt you know that? The enemy is the heart. And all you can do is propitiate the darkness there‚Ä¶ as Thorpe arrived in black linen jacket, red T-shirt, nose stud, eyes eager, and Highet‚Äôs demeanor switched to the cheerful, ‚ÄìJef, my man. I want to wow the rubes when we go to the desert. We have a ranch out there with a data feed from the test site. What can you do that‚Äôs portable and fantastic? I want flash that makes you reach for your checkbook.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHey, I‚Äôve got an interface toolkit from my CodeWin days, I can throw something together overnight. Just tell me what kind of data I have to work with.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôll e-mail the details. Shot‚Äôs tomorrow evening, you‚Äôll have to get a plane out by noon to set up. Not too much for you, is it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìDemo or die, I know the drill, said Thorpe, grinning.</p>
<hr />
<p>The evening wind whipped dust across the flat stretch of highway, slowing traffic and shuddering the shells of cars backed up across three lanes behind flashing lights at EXIT NLY CODOR IC S as Quine punched ‚Äìillion in property loss, over to ‚Äìnoninjury accident being cleared at the Codornices Road exit not blocking lanes for you, drowned in a siren blaring up the shoulder OHLONE VALLEY RESCUE ECNALUBMA as Quine edged against horns and unheard curses into the exit lane and cut back on a commercial strip to loop up behind the central mall the reverse of whose colonnaded [pg256] and pedimented facade, raw concrete stained by long ago rains, caught with a sort of wounded dignity the sun‚Äôs last rays as they lanced past Estancia Estates An Adult Community where Quine parked and for a moment held in his gaze a prospect of bungalows arrayed on lawns billiardgreen out to their surveyed boundary of dry pasture before ascending the walk and ringing the bell.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh! Philip. Come in. I wasn‚Äôt expecting you.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWell it‚Äôs Friday night, I thought</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh I‚Äôm glad you, but just, if you‚Äôd called I would have made dinner‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìI wasn‚Äôt sure I was coming.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYour work is done?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThere‚Äôs a test. I fly out tomorrow afternoon. And there‚Äôs a presentation Monday.</p>
<p>‚ÄìCan you stay tonight? We can go out for‚Ä¶ is something wrong?</p>
<p>‚ÄìCan I ask who‚Äôs the guy with the curly black hair and the good tan?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe, what?</p>
<p>‚ÄìI happened to see you both the other day. In a hallway. He was acting pretty proprietary.</p>
<p>‚ÄìProprie‚Ä¶ Nan‚Äôs face flushed.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHow long has this been going on?</p>
<p>‚ÄìHis name‚Äôs Ben and he‚Äôs a good friend, and it‚Äôs been‚Ä¶ we‚Äôve been friends for years. Five years at least. Since before I knew you.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou still see him?</p>
<p>The flush darkened, and her mild features contorted into an anger he‚Äôd never seen in her. ‚ÄìYou mean, do I sleep with him? Yes, I have, once or twice since you and I have been together.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOnce or twice. You‚Äôve lost count.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh, Philip! Why are you, this is hateful!</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt hurts me, Nan.</p>
<p>Her face was a mask of plain misery. ‚ÄìWe never</p>
<p>‚ÄìNever what, laid down rules? No, I didn‚Äôt think we had to, I thought some things went without saying.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWithout saying what! that I‚Äôm yours alone when you don‚Äôt give me anything, not even a word of love, for God‚Äôs sake Philip I didn‚Äôt turn to Ben for sex, just for, for kindness, to feel that I <em>mattered</em> to someone! A year, almost two years of my life Philip, I‚Äôm no longer a young woman, do you want to know when it was I saw Ben, when it was I went to him after you and I were together?</p>
<p>The coldness, the absolute coldness of the moment.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou don‚Äôt even care do you. When we met, at the Labor Day picnic two years ago, and I was so charmed by you, your intelligence, your modesty, [pg257] yoru reserve. Do you remember, there was a thunderstorm? I hadn‚Äôt seen one since moving West. And you took me home, we were drenched, and I loaned you clothes. Oh Philip, it was over between Ben and me he was like a brother, I just wanted to, I don‚Äôt know, say good-bye, tell someone close to me how happy I thought I‚Äôd be.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAnd the second time?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, a year later, when you didn‚Äôt come to dinner, didn‚Äôt call, and I waited and waited so it was only an anniversary just a date on the calendar that‚Äôs all but I called Ben and he came over to be with me, and he didn‚Äôt, didn‚Äôt even <em>want</em>‚Ä¶ cut off by her sobs, jagged and piercing.</p>
<p>‚ÄìBut I, you knew I was in a meeting, you could have</p>
<p>‚ÄìAnd you call him proprietary! When you come here and, and sulk for hours, barely acknowledge my existence, don‚Äôt call for days on end, and then expect, how do you think that makes me feel‚Ä¶ cut by sobs, ‚Äìand you‚Äôve never, never asked me what I want, how I feel, I would have told you about Ben if you‚Äôd asked if you‚Äôd shown any interest at all in my past. I don‚Äôt think you know who I am!</p>
<p>Within him a stone fell and fell, soundlessly turning.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPhilip, talk to me! Don‚Äôt turn off like this!</p>
<p>‚ÄìI have nothing to say, and he was out the door, where streetlights had come on, knowing that his leaving was a catastrophe more final than anything gone before, a withdrawal he could never make right. Don‚Äôt tell me, don‚Äôt tell me we don‚Äôt feed the emptiness in each other. Betrayal is an aether through which an energy moves.</p>
</section>
<section id="section-4" class="level3">
<h3>5</h3>
<p>One hundred miles from Mesa Encantada, whose tracts of waste and infecund desert had been reclaimed for science as Site 600, was the Advanced Research Institute of the Eastern Sierra, a ranch at the edge of the Owens Valley, a black facility whose funding appeared in no budget. Deeded to the government by a conservative rancher, it served as a layover site for Lab personnel on their way to the desert. It nestled in the broad base of a canyon near a creek‚Äôs loud runoff through lateral moraine. To the west the ground rose in the space of a few miles from six thousand feet to a twelve thousand foot crest of granite crags. Below, to the east, the highway lay like a ribbon dropped across the wrinkled valley floor, and a hundred miles farther across desert dotted with sage under a flotilla of thunderheads was Mesa Encantada.</p>
<p>Even before the Labs, Quine had seen ARIES. On his first trip west, while switching planes at Phoenix, he‚Äôd been paged and diverted to a single-engine craft bound for a Kern County airstrip, where a sheriff‚Äôs four [pg258] by four awaited him. The first Radiance shot had just gone off and at the ranch they were celebrating. Quine met Highet there as he beat a twelve-year-old at chess, telling the boy, I‚Äôll trade a bishop for a knight anytime, I love knights, they leap barriers, they face eight ways at once.</p>
<p>A month after that he was at the Mesa. Rank smell of sage hovered in the predawn cool, immensities of desert air quivered to the horizon. They drove upcanyon with the sun rising behind him, the young initiates joking, group leaders and guards and observers in DoD hardhats silent and grim. Roadways of cables led from instrument trailers over desert pocked with the collapsed craters of previous tests to the distant borehole. Above it a red crane pointing straight up. The count reached zero. And the earth rippled. A wave rushed toward them and the ground shook as if a train were passing and passing and passing. When it stopped the air was a clear plasma of exaltation. To know that the binding forces of matter were yours to break, the wealth of nations yours to drive into such sublime force, this was a deep and secret sweetness known only to the few.</p>
<p>At the ranch now Thorpe was joking with some grad students from X Section. Others were there from J Section, and some stern faces he didn‚Äôt know, military or intelligence, and Steradian alert as a corrupt deputy. Highet arrived in black Western shirt with red and white embroidery across the yoke, blue jeans, and tooled leather boots, carrying cases of soda, chanting in a false twang, ‚ÄìTwaace the sugar, twaace the caffeine‚Ä¶ followed by a Western senator, cadaverous and grinning in white Stetson, and his young aide plump and groomed to a sheen, with the zealous black eyes of a pullet.</p>
<p>‚ÄìLook at em, young, brilliant, confident, said the senator. ‚ÄìThat‚Äôs how I felt at their age. They own the world.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe world? retorted Highet. ‚ÄìThey own their genitals. The rest of them‚Äôs mine, raising his voice to introduce, ‚ÄìGentlemen, the right honorable Howard Bangerter, R-Utah‚Ä¶</p>
<p>The aide asked if physics had yet succeeded in finding in the traces of Creation the fingerprints of God, and Highet nodded, a slow smile spreading and his tonguetip darting as his hands rose to conjure, ‚ÄìNot God exactly‚Ä¶ as Quine walked onto the deck where three barbecue grills sizzled, and a keg of Coors Lite sat amidst greasy paper plates bearing the ruins of meals, and the sun had long since chased the waning moon, itself pursuing Venus, behind the mountain wall. Although the sky retained day‚Äôs blue a chill came down from the remote snowless peaks.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThis young man, Highet‚Äôs voice carried out from within, won last year‚Äôs Heinrich Hertz Fellowship in Physics, a prestigious award I happen to administer‚Ä¶ and Quine stepped down from the deck, crossing dry grass to the creek‚Äôs rockstrewn willowed bank where it trickled through [pg259] small pools and clumps of rotting leaves. Quine followed it up, breath laboring. He stopped at a large boulder long ago frostwedged and tumbled from a higher place, and sat. No residue of warmth. The western ridge was a great dark wave. In the east a glamour of rosetint clouds swept up from the horizon. The ranch was small below him. A wind came down the great wall of rock. Into this chaos he might ascend and be lost.</p>
<p>But he did not. He returned to the ranch, Thorpe‚Äôs voice coming as he slid open the glass doors, ‚Äìbackground, trucks on the highway, that sort of thing. Other side of the spool you can see some small temblors we had this afternoon. When the shot goes off we‚Äôll definitely see more than a wiggle. But the real action‚Äôs on screen. At the site they‚Äôre recording everything for later analysis but data‚Äôs also piped to this workstation where autocorrelation software I wrote gives us an immediate window on what‚Äôs happening. Red is intense energy, blue less intense. We‚Äôre looking for a red ringlike structure.</p>
<p>Quine watched the stylus quiver as about him others conversed. Without warning the stylus jerked. The screen of the workstation came to life, numbers flowing down its right edge. Colors coalesced fitfully on screen. The senator and his aide leaned in enrapt. A minute passed. Blue and green surrounded a corona of yellow and a jagged red core flecked with white.</p>
<p>‚ÄìWe have brightness, Thorpe said. ‚ÄìA hundred times the last test. More. Maybe a thousand times.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThree orders of magnitude improvement in six months, declared Highet. ‚ÄìAt this rate we‚Äôll have every enemy missile on Earth neutralized in a few years, and raising his tone with his glass, ‚ÄìTo Team Radiance! Leonardos of the age. You people are the best in the world.</p>
<p>Grunts and howls of triumph went off like rockets.</p>
<p>‚ÄìDo you all know what we‚Äôve done? We‚Äôve broken the back of Communism. And that‚Äôs only so far.</p>
<p>More applause. The senator‚Äôs aide leaned smiling to whisper in the senator‚Äôs ear.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNeed now‚Äôs a nice little war where we can demo this stuff. Feed some tinhorn tyrant some antiquated missiles and provoke him to use them.</p>
<p>A second wave of guests arrived, a dozen men in suits adorned with MAMMOTH CONVENTION CENTER NAME COMPANY and a few women packaged as brightly as new software, and Quine moved off through the manic younger men hopped up by caffeine and sugar and the shot.</p>
<p>‚ÄìPDP downstairs running spacewar</p>
<p>‚Äìthought Malibu was bad but Acapulco‚Äôs about three inch waves</p>
<p>‚Äìblasts wheat into stubble in a shock tube at mach ten, that‚Äôs his study, eighty k a year</p>
<p>‚Äìmaybe the moon‚Äôs changed its orbit or [pg260]</p>
<p>‚Äìtranslate the project into terms attractive to DARPA</p>
<p>‚Äìwell Mazatlan then or Valparaiso</p>
<p>‚Äìthink I‚Äôll propose rye</p>
<p>‚Äìdup rot swap drop</p>
