<p>‚Äìseme-e?</p>
<p>‚ÄìGo for it, Bruno, do the meat thing.</p>
<p>Quine edged into a hallway and down a narrow flight of stairs as behind him music began pounding, catching as he turned a last glimpse of Thorpe, cheeks flushed, smiling at a circle of admirers the impartial smile of triumph.</p>
<p><em>Nature is more ready in her creating than time in his destroying, and so she has ordained that many animals shall be food for others.</em></p>
<p>He continued downstairs toward a light. In the cellar seven or eight young men from X Section were gathered around an old rackmounted minicomputer and a pool table.</p>
<p>‚Äìso he goes, learn to hassle people and lie with a straight face.</p>
<p>‚ÄìExcuse me, I need to get back. Does anyone know the arrangements?</p>
<p>‚ÄìExcellent advice, dude.</p>
<p>‚ÄìExcuse</p>
<p>One glanced up. ‚ÄìThere‚Äôs pool cars outside somewhere.</p>
<p>Full dark. A dozen cars. E108637. DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY OFFICIAL [pg262] USE ONLY. Key in the column. The seat harness slid up and drew in over his chest and waist as a chime sounded and dash lights blinked red then glowed teal. The car swayed and bounced for a mile down the dirt road. There the highway stretched north and south into void, under stars like chips of ice. He could go anywhere. But time was a field that moved with him, inescapable, close as the blue light in the cabin. He drove for hours without stopping, radio for company, wash of noise, hollowness in his being. Mountains that a century ago killed emigrants with their rigors fell to his vehicle. Descending to the flats, he saw brushfires crawling brightly on far ridges like luminous protolife, like the fitful colors on Thorpe‚Äôs screen from the bad sensors, and the fires fell away behind him and the farm cities loomed on the ancient seabed, their lights and capillary highways glowing with perfervid intensity in the unnatural warmth persisting from this arid summer long past its term, its heat bonded to the earth like some toxin to a susceptible organ, and booming through the car‚Äôs windows when he opened them was the smell of dust, manure, smoke, exhaust, chemicals, and he crossed the last ridge to arrive in his valley of a million souls, of all the places he might go, for all the freedom he had, here again.</p>
<p>In the dark apartment he stripped, trailing damp rank clothes to the bathroom. The mirror‚Äôs sudden light showed him, before selfhood interposed its protective assurance, the face of a stranger, aging and vulnerable. The soft flesh of his body was without tone or color. Lowering his eyes from the harsh brightness he stood voiding for long seconds. A ribbon of urine twisted along the axis of its arc as it splashed into the bowl. Standing thus he blinked, faded, woke. The gates of sleep stood open and he was through them, uncleansed, as soon as he lay down.</p>
<p>On a moonless night at the edge of a forest there is the slap and sizzle of rainfall. A moist breeze springs up. Yet where he stands, in long grass, all is dry. Only in the forest is it raining. A figure in the forest shadows stands regarding him. It holds an offering of some kind, a gift. He does not move to take the gift, and shortly the figure recedes into the forest.</p>
</section>
<section id="section-5" class="level3">
<h3>6</h3>
<p>Gathering before dawn the crowd set out for the main gate, to be met by police as unceasing arrivals swelled it further, until Lab workers began to show up in their vehicles and county and city police were called to divert traffic to the north gate against the columns of people still coming, and the south road was closed to vehicles and state police summoned, and still the spectacle slowed traffic to walking speed, so that Quine was late to Highet‚Äôs office where Highet stared out his window at the south road.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThose people out there will never understand. It could be so much [pg263] worse. On the other side, entire cities, entire regions have no civilian industry at all, it‚Äôs all military. Here we cut our deals as needed but we still do real science. We bring in people like you. We roll back the darkness.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThere‚Äôs a problem.</p>
<p>Highet turned. ‚ÄìWhat.</p>
<p>‚ÄìThe beryllium and hydrogen sensors were cabled separately. Thorpe‚Äôs analysis at the ranch used only the beryllium. I looked at the hydrogen data yesterday. No brightness. No beam. Nothing there.</p>
<p>Nodding, Highet turned again to the window. ‚ÄìI see. The hydrogen sensors which I asked you not to use. You know, I almost stopped that work order, came that close. But I wanted to see what you had in mind.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAs supervisor it was my decision.</p>
<p>‚ÄìOn your head be it. Where‚Äôs your quantitative agreement now?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou saw at the ranch. The beryllium shows it. Spectrum peaks as predicted. But that‚Äôs not a focused X-ray, that‚Äôs oxygen in the beryllium glowing at just the right wavelength. It looks exactly like the new model‚Äôs predictions for focus.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAnd where did this new model come from?</p>
<p>‚ÄìThorpe‚Äôs been modifying my code. I found a routine where just this set of frequencies is amplified. You‚Äôll find that my copies of the files haven‚Äôt been modified for ten days.</p>
<p>Highet came from the window, pacing past the photos of presidents and artists‚Äô renderings, touching the length of cable.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI see. Well, this is bad for him, you know. Especially after Fish and Himmelhoch. He has a history.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI wouldn‚Äôt call it intentional. The ideas he brought were good. I worked with him, I didn‚Äôt see this, it could have happened to anyone.</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt doesn‚Äôt matter. He has a history, voice sharpening, ‚Äìquackery or carelessness, you think it matters? You think you can ever walk away from your history?</p>
<p>Quine said nothing.</p>
<p>‚ÄìNow those hydrogen sensors, you piggybacked your own little test onto the piggyback, that was very cute. Did Thorpe know about that?</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou saw the work orders.</p>
<p>‚ÄìHe knew he was getting feed from the beryllium only?</p>
<p>‚ÄìIt was his demo.</p>
<p>‚ÄìYes, you saw to that. All right. We‚Äôll keep him on for a while. Then you‚Äôll write him a letter of recommendation. Down the road we‚Äôll issue a report on the false brightness. You‚Äôll be group leader on that. Highet‚Äôs voice was tight with controlled fury. ‚ÄìYou begin to interest me, Philip. I thought I knew what to expect from you.</p>
<p>‚ÄìAt least we caught this now. [pg264]</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh no we haven‚Äôt. We haven‚Äôt caught a thing yet.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI don‚Äôt want to sound naive, you‚Äôre not going to mention this at the presentation?</p>
<p>‚ÄìToday? I think not. I think I will not at this time give the enemies of reason grounds sufficient to bury an entire body of knowledge and aspiration. Highet lifted from his desk a small device etched with a craft undreamed of even a decade before, raising it before him like a talisman, then replaced it and gazed at Quine implacably. ‚ÄìI believe not.</p>
<p>The telephone rang and Highet lifted it in midring, ‚ÄìNo I can‚Äôt see anyone right now, as Nolan came through the door bearing a red folder, acknowledging Quine with a minute change of expression.</p>
<p>‚ÄìVery clean data from your shot, said Nolan.</p>
<p>‚Äìno damn it Senator Chase is coming in an hour</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh, you‚Äôve seen it?</p>
<p>‚ÄìWe prepared the overheads. A match with theory unparalleled since Mendel‚Äôs peas. Kid‚Äôs a barn burner is he?</p>
<p>‚Äìwhat do you mean here now? We‚Äôre not set up</p>
<p>‚ÄìHe‚Äôd like to be.</p>
<p>‚Äìdamn it keep him down there</p>
<p>‚ÄìYou‚Äôre taking him under your wing.</p>
<p>‚Äìfucking lantern-jawed hero of the people can just wait</p>
<p>‚ÄìMy political skills are legendary, Quine joked.</p>
<p>‚Äìdon‚Äôt care! Do whatever it takes! I‚Äôll call you when we‚Äôre ready.</p>
<p>‚ÄìI‚Äôve noticed, Nolan said, turning to Highet as he put down the phone.</p>
<p>‚Äìhave to do everyone‚Äôs job, what‚Äôs this?</p>
<p>‚ÄìOverheads of the Taliesin data.</p>
<p>‚ÄìFine, just leave them. Bernd there you are find the rest of the team will you get them up here we have a little problem god damn senator from the liberal east arrived just a little ahead of schedule he‚Äôs downsta, Aron where the hell have you been we‚Äôve got a PR‚Ä¶ Nolan!_-</p>
<p>‚ÄìOh! I just, sorry, didn‚Äôt see your foot</p>
<p>‚ÄìJeez sorry Aron let me help you up‚Ä¶</p>
<p>‚ÄìNolan will you get the hell</p>
<p>‚Äìmy slides! here don‚Äôt step on</p>
<p>‚ÄìNolan!</p>
<p>‚Äìjust put these back in order, with the ah integrated twenty-four-bit color TGIF animations and music in standard MIDI files</p>
<p>‚ÄìAron</p>
<p>‚Äìlittle problem with the synthesizer all the instruments stuck on the cowbell patch so when we played the <em>Apocalypse Now</em> music, the Wager Valk, rather intriguing actually but hardly [pg265]</p>
